<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan, U.S. to Improve Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev held talks here today with the delegation of the
U.S. International Relations Committee on furthering bilateral
economic ties.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Chairman of the U.S. International Economic
Relations Committee Peter Peterson told reporters that the most
important task now for Kazakhstan, which declared independence
more than five years ago, is to attract foreign investment
</P>
<P>
He said the United States, as Kazakhstan's biggest investor,
would strengthen cooperation with the Central Asian country in the
oil and natural gas industry and help it establish securities
market.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, headed by Peterson and David Rockefeller,
honorary chairman of the U.S. committee, arrived here earlier
today for a two-day visit to Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The committee, set up in 1921, is a non-business and
non-governmental organization aimed at promoting dialogue between
the United States and other countries and helping the
U.S. businesses expand to the rest of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
