<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Cyprus Coordinator Arrives for Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Special Coordinator for
Cyprus, Thomas Miller, today called on parties involved in the
Cyprus problem to focus their attention on efforts to facilitate
a solution and avoid dealing with pedantics.
</P>
<P>
Miller made the call upon his arrival in Cyprus on the last
leg of his current regional tour which had taken him to Ankara
and Athens.
</P>
<P>
Miller said his visit to Cyprus, which is the first one since
his appointment a couple of months ago, is "to do a lot of
listening".
</P>
<P>
He said "President Bill Clinton is very very interested in
coming up with a solution to the Cyprus problem and Secretary of
State Albright is intimately familiar with the issues, and very
very interested in working to facilitate a solution to a problem
that has gone on far too long."
</P>
<P>
Noting this period is "critical", Miller said a lot of work
needs to be done, and added "I know that any difficult problem,
and most definitely the Cyprus problem is in that category,
necessitates a certain give-and-take by the parties."
</P>
<P>
"No-one gets everything they want, that is the definition
of a successful negotiation," he remarked.
</P>
<P>
He described his talks in Ankara as "very productive", and in
Athens as "excellent", but refrained from disclosing any details
about the discussions.
</P>
<P>
Miller is scheduled to have meetings with Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Miller's visit came following the two rounds of U.N.-led
direct talks between Clerides and Denktash in July and August,
which ended in failure.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official is expected to make preparations for a visit
to the region by U.S. Presidential Emissary on Cyprus, Richard
Holbrooke, scheduled for later this year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey sent troops
and took over one third of the island nation in the wake of a
failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece. The
United Nations and the international community have been working
for decades to reunite the Turkish Cypriot north and Greek Cypriot
south, but so far no concrete results have been achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
