<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM Satisfied with European Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides today expressed satisfaction with his European
tour, saying the outcome of the tour was "positive."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Cyprus radio, the foreign minister
said he was satisfied with the contacts with his European
counterparts and the assurances by officials who had recently
expressed negative views on Cyprus' European Union (EU) accession
course.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides' tour was mainly aimed at discussing the issue of
Cyprus' bid to become a European Union member.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot foreign minister expected that the EU will make a
decision in December on when to start accession talks with
candidate countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU reaffirmed its decision in July that the accession
talks with Cyprus will begin in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
With regard to a formula about the participation of Turkish
Cypriots in the accession talks, he said when the Turkish
Cypriot community accepts the principle of entry into the EU and
its representation as part of the official Cyprus delegation,
"there are ways for Turkish Cypriots to participate."
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that during his 13-day tour which
concluded today, he had the chance to calm down concerns
expressed by the EU member states on the deployment of the
Russian S-300 anti-aircraft missiles in Cyprus in mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government will negotiate a solution to the Cyprus
problem with "good will and a constructive spirit" and once a
proposal by Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides for the island's
demilitarization was accepted, there would be no need for the
deployment of the surface-to-air missiles, Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Kasoulides was due in Athens today on his
way back home to brief Greek officials on the outcome of his
European tour, which had taken him to Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania,
Germany, Luxembourg and Italy.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to meet with his Greek counterpart Theodoros
Pangalos, Foreign Under-Secretary Yiannos Kranidiotis and
Alternate Foreign Minister George Papandreou to discuss issues
including Turkey's threats for the "gradual integration" of
northern Cyprus with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
took over the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally a breakaway "The
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which has been
recognized only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
