<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improvement of Productivity Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 12 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean economist today
said organized labor, private sector and the government should
realize the need for high productivity facing strong competition
stemming from the opening up of most sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
John Makamure, chief economist of the Zimbabwe National
Chamber of Commerce, noted that lack of effective communication
between management and staff stifles efforts by companies to
boost productivity and improve the quality of products.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''lack of communication has been the major handicap
to efforts to improve productivity and what we need is a clear
sense of direction and commitment from both management and
employees.''
</P>
<P>
Makamure pointed out that most companies had, instead of
addressing the issue of productivity, resorted to other
cost-cutting measures that included down-sizing and
retrenchments.
</P>
<P>
''Despite these measures, they are still unable to compete
against products from other parts of the world because all
important decisions affecting company are not communicated to the
lower level employees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Makamure's comments follow recent moves by the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) to improve productivity in
the region widely viewed as the future economic hub of the
continent.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is the only member of the regional grouping which
has established a productivity institute while other member
states have in principle shown interest in setting up similar
organizations to spearhead research in this area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
