<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Crackdown on Illegal Alcohol Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin today urged a crackdown on illegal trafficking in alcohol
and tougher controls on domestic sales.
</P>
<P>
In a routine national speech on radio, Yeltsin said the alcohol
industries suffered a decline in production and experienced sharp
losses in profits because of illegal production and smuggling and
sales of unlicensed and unauthorized alcohol.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin rated the crime second only to economic swindling,
which has caused huge economic losses to the country. The crime
has profited illegal traffickers and corrupt officials while the
country's revenues have been reduced by half, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the dangers of the "bootleg" alcohol to human
health. The mortality of alcoholism has doubled over the recent
five years in Russia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin made a similar appeal last December and enacted
relevant laws and regulations. But enforcement was not too
effective since one-third of the sales of Russian alcohol is still
under the control of illegal traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that 30 to 50 percent of the alcohol in the
current Russian market is of inferior quality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
