<HEADLINE> Clinton, Tung Emphasize US-Chinese Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region met here today, emphasizing the importance
of a good US-Chinese relationship.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting at the White House,
Tung said that he had a "warm and cordial" meeting with Clinton at
the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
The discussed generally about Asia and the importance of a good
Sino-US relationship.
</P>
<P>
"The president emphasized how important the relationship is for
the world, and I emphasized how important it is for Hong Kong,"
Tung told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by Clinton's senior aides,
including Vice President Al Gore, Clinton's national security
advisor Sandy Berger, and Daniel Tarullo, the president's advisor
for international economy.
</P>
<P>
They also talked about how important the coming summit between
Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin in October would be,
Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope and expect the coming summit between President Jiang
Zemin and President Clinton and will be a successful one," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"We also had opportunity for me to emphasize how important the
U.S.-Hong Kong relationship is," he told reporters. "I emphasize
we will do the utmost to make sure that the relationship continues
to be strong and viable."
</P>
<P>
"I have also emphasized our commitment to democracy and to the
movement of political evolution as outlined in the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tung briefed Clinton and his aides on the situation
in Hong Kong and cooperation between the US and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
They discussed the intellectual property right protection, the
strategic commodity trade curb and fight against drug smuggling,
he said. "In all the areas, we can work together."
</P>
<P>
"I was able to explain to the president how well the transition
has gone and that the (policy of) `one country, two systems' is
functioning very well," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Tung noted that he explained his commitment to democracy, and
to the movement of political evolution as outlined in the Basic
Law. "We are moving forward in democracy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung arrived here Monday and traveled to New York Thursday and
returned today for the meeting with Clinton. He is leaving
Washington for home this noon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
