<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Joins Shanghai Delegates in Panel Discussion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Jiang Zemin took part in
a panel disucssion here with the Party congress delegates from
Shanghai, China's largest industrial city, after giving a
two-and-half hour report this morning to the 2,000-plus delegates
from across the country.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of China opened its 15th national congress
here today.
</P>
<P>
As soon as he stepped into the meeting room at 3:00 p.m., Jiang
caught of Xia Zhengnong, 93, a specially invited delegate who once
served as secretary of the Shanghai Municipal Party Committee.
</P>
<P>
After whishing Xia good health, Jiang said he came to
listen to opinions of other delegates.
</P>
<P>
After Han Zhen, director of the Shanghai Planning Commission,
briefed him on the latest achievements Shanghai has scored in
economic development and urban construction, Jiang asked Han about
the average living space for each Shanghai citizen. Han told him
that it is about 8.6 square meters and the figure is expected to
reach ten.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, manager of a local shipping company and director of
a local neigborhood committee spoke on issue of the cultural and
ethical progress.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin said,"As a member of the Communist Party, we should
always work for the benefits of the people."
</P>
<P>
Liu Jinghai, a middle school principal from Zhabei District,
Shanghai, briefed Jiang and other delegates on the better living
conditions for teachers.
</P>
<P>
After hearing that there are two teachers with doctors degrees
and 29 with masters degrees in the middle schools and primary
schools in the district, Jiang said,"It is an encouraging sign
which means there is no lack of successors."
</P>
<P>
After hearing talks by Shanghai delegates, Jiang extended his
thanks to the Party delegates who are working in the grassroots
levels. He urged local people to work harder to train more people
so as to better build Shanghai and serve other parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
"Nowadays, science and technology are developing quite rapidly
and new knowledge is emerging in an endless stream," Jiang said.
"And therefore no one is too old to learn," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
