<HEADLINE> UNESCO Sub-regional Workshop Ends in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 12 (Xinhua) -- A five-day UNESCO
sub-regional workshop aimed at redressing the imbalance in
scientific, technical and vocational education for girls in
Africa ended here today.
</P>
<P>
In his closing remarks, Zimbabwe's Education, Sport and
Culture Deputy Minister Kembo Mohadi said time for rhetoric was
over, and it was time to translate words into action.
</P>
<P>
He said while something had been done in the different
countries attending the workshop to redress the imbalances by
including women in vocational, scientific, and technological
education, more still had to be done.
</P>
<P>
Mohadi said the workshop which came soon after the 8th
congress of the Pan-African Women's Congress held in Harare in
August, also sought to complete and implement some relevant
issues and resolutions raised in that congress.
</P>
<P>
The delegates at the workshop discussed strategies for
bringing girls into science education, viable alternatives in
science education and vocational training for girls, plan of
action and agenda for the future as well as sharing experiences.
</P>
<P>
the workshop attracted some 30 delegates from Uganda,
Tanzania, Kenya, South Africa, Zambia, Swaziland, Lesotho,
Mozambique, Botswana, Malawi, Ghana and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
