<HEADLINE> Opening of CPC National Congress Hailed by Mao's Countrymen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- This morning, Mao's
Restaurant in Shaoshanchong Village, central China's Hunan Province,
the native place of late Chinese leader Mao Zedong, was packed
with government officials and villagers.
</P>
<P>
They came not to eat but to watch the live telecast of the
opening of the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) in the capital of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"We could feel the festival mood by sitting together to watch
the opening of the Party Congress," said Mao Weiren, a 27-year man
from the village, where the Chinese leader was born in December
26, 1893.
</P>
<P>
People in Mao's hometown have become well-off: 100 percent of
the families there having TVs -- 60 percent are color -- and the
majority have moved into new houses. Some have even bought their own
cars, according to the young man.
</P>
<P>
Tang Ruiren, the owner of the well-known Mao's Restaurant, told
Xinhua, "Jiang Zemin's report at the congress has soothed us a
lot."
</P>
<P>
She said that a stable national policy would boost her
business. Tang plans to start two branches in other cities soon.
</P>
<P>
While news from the congress is comforting to Mao's countrymen,
it has turned the ethnic minority-dominated Tongdao Dong
Nationality Autonomous County, also in Hunan, into a land of song
and dance.
</P>
<P>
Local officials and ordinary people gathered at Xinzhai Village
in the county to celebrate the opening of the Congress. "My family
has been well-off, thanks to the good policies of the Party," said
Li Benzheng, a villager, whose family used to rely on government
subsidies before the reform began in 1978, but now earns over
20,000 yuan (2,400 US dollars) per year.
</P>
<P>
"Jiang's report at the Congress has made us more confident in
the future," said Yang Zenggang, secretary of the village Party
Branch Committee. "In the next stage, we plan to introduce foreign
funds to open factories manufacturing timber products and pumps."
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
