<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Climate Outlook Forum Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The five-day Southern African
Regional Climate Outlook Forum ended in Kadoma, central Zimbabwe
today with meteorological and weather experts agreeing the region
is likely to experience below to near normal rainfall this year.
</P>
<P>
The forum which was convened to formulate a consensus guidance
for the coming rainy season in southern Africa was held against a
background of the El Nino phenomenon which is reported to be
growing in the tropical Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is the warming of sea waters disrupting rainfall
clouds leading to the unleashing of disasters such as droughts
and floods throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
In the first period, which is October to December, above
normal rainfall is expected to fall.
</P>
<P>
''Even for Zimbabwe, the beginning of the rainy season is
expected to be good,'' Marufu Zinyowera, director of
meteorological services in Zimbabwe told the Zimbabwe News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
''But it is also expected to drastically drop to far below
normal soon after Christmas, so we are advising farmers not to
use long season crops,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is expected to receive a 33 percent of below to near
normal rainfall this season which has been feared to be the
lowest ever.
</P>
<P>
''Although the seasonal onset may be favorable, the
possibility of a later downward trend should be considered. There
are extremes such as the southern tip of South Africa, where
above normal rainfall is expected,'' said Zinyowera.
</P>
<P>
The experts report, however, differs completely with a report
from the center for environmental studies at the University of
Zululand in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The report said Zimbabwe would experience below normal
rainfall by 57 percent in the early summer but was expected to
improve drastically assuring farmers of an above normal season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Retail Sales Increase for 3rd Straight Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in the U.S.
rose by 0.4 percent in August, the third straight increase, the
U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that retail sales totaled a seasonally
adjusted 213.7 billion dollars in the month, up from a revised
212.8 billion in July. The July figure was initially estimated to
be 212.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The August increase in retail sales followed larger jumps of
0.7 percent in June and the revised 0.9 percent in July. The
retail sales declined from the March to May which had slowed U.S.
economic growth from a strong 4.9 percent annual rate during the
first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that all sectors shared in the latest advance
except for food.
</P>
<P>
The increases in U.S. retail sales was led by sales of durable
goods -- items expected to last more than three years. It rose by
0.7 percent after gaining 1.3 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Automobile sales were up 0.8 percent after a 1.8 percent
increase in July. Excluding autos, retail sales were still up 0.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales of nondurable goods such as food and fuel rose by a
modest 0.2 percent in August after a 0.6 percent gain in the
previous month. But grocery stores reported a 0.2 percent loss in
sales for August, following a 0.4 percent increase in July.
</P>
<P>
Department store sales were up 0.6 percent after a 0.8 percent
increase in July. Gas station sales rose 0.5 percent in August
following a 0.7 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts said strong sales alone won't convince the U.S.
Federal Reserve to raise interest rates again when its
policy-maker -- the Open Market Committee -- meets on September
30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: ALbright's Mediation Gets Nowhere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The much publicized
mediation efforts by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
between the Israelis and Palestinians concluded today without
making any headway in reviving the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
An visibly upset Albright, virtually empty-handed in her first
visit to the region after becoming the U.S. top diplomat, did not
conceal her dissatisfaction and disappointment with the failure of
her efforts, which had been so widely expected to bring new hope
to break the prolonged and dangerous deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Ramallah today after her second and
last meeting in three days with Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat, ALbright said that only little
progress had been made in her efforts to bring the two sides back
to negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
She was referring to the scheduled meeting in Washington
late this month between two Israeli and Palestinian teams led
by senior aides to Israeli and PNA leaders. Another top
meeting between Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and PNA
deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (or Abu Mazen) was also planned later
this month in New York during the United Nations General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"But I do think there is a great deal to be done
here, and I am obviously not satisfied. Big steps are needed
and we will be able to take small ones," she said.
</P>
<P>
To hammer home her message of disappointment, Albright warned
that she was not ready to return to the region unless the
two sides take big steps to proceed. "I am not coming back
to tread water," she said bluntly.
</P>
<P>
Seemingly, the failure of Albright's mediation was attributed
to the stances of intransigency taken by both Israel and
the PNA, which have established respective preconditions for
resuming the peace talks. Israel demanded the PNA launch an
all-out war against terrorism, while the PNA insisted that
Israel should first lift its sanctions and fulfill its
commitments to the signed peace accords.
</P>
<P>
However, the true reason for Albright's failure in resuming
the peace process should be traced back to herself since she
has adopted an apparently biased attitude in favor of Israel
from the start of her mediation here.
</P>
<P>
In her statements made after meeting Israeli President Ezer
Weizman Wednesday right upon her arrival, Albright deliberately
stressed the unique and strategically important relations between
Israel and the U.S., vowing to support Israel economically,
politically and militarily.
</P>
<P>
She also expressed the U.S. unequivocal support to Israel's
demand on the PNA's fighting terrorism, while neglecting the PNA
pleas for more U.S. pressure to lift Israel's unjustified
sanctions and violations of Oslo accords, such as continuing
settlement activities and delaying further troop withdrawal in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Even Israeli officials, originally bracing for tough U.S.
pressure, were stunned by Albright's warmth and understanding
towards Israel at a time when the world expected the U.S.
to play the role of an impartial mediator to monitor the
implementation of the signed agreements under its auspices.
</P>
<P>
Only until Thursday evening did Albright make a low-key
speech, in which she criticized Israel for taking some
unilateral steps to preempt issues reserved for the final-status
negotiations, including settlement construction, land confiscation
and demolition of Arab houses.
</P>
<P>
Albright's failure was also because she had not succeeded
in securing a freeze, even temporarily, on Israel's settlement
activities. Undoubtedly, the current crisis in the peace process
was caused by Israel's building of the Har Homa settlement
in East Jerusalem in March, and the recent wave of suicide
bombings in Jerusalem have only aggravated the tension.
</P>
<P>
Albright only said that Israel should refrain from taking
unilateral steps to preempt the final negotiations in order
to create a proper environment for the peace process to
blossom.
</P>
<P>
Albright's failure and her threat to stay away from the process
was an ominous sign for the moribund Israeli-Palestinian peace
process, which could slide backwards into the abyss of more
violence and widespread confrontations in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EMU Will Cut Dole Queues in Europe, Says Flynn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The European single currency
will help to solve Europe's unemployment problems and cannot be
seen as an "optional extra," Padraig Flynn, the European Union's
social affairs commissioner, has told an annual conference.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that establishing a single currency will not be
enough on its own to safeguard employment and growth across
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing session of the Trade Union Congress's
annual congress which ended Thursday, Flynn said he would be
launching a new European social program next year which would draw
up a set of guidelines with boosting employment as its main aim.
</P>
<P>
He made clear that the EU was not planning to use the social
chapter to introduce new laws. There was "no conspiracy and no
hidden agenda" to burden EU countries with new restrictions.
</P>
<P>
But Flynn added, "Let me be clear: if action is necessary, I
will not hesitate to propose the appropriate legislation and to
promote it."
</P>
<P>
He said, "Our objective must be a full economic and monetary
union, with positive coordination of national policies and
objectives, including employment, as well as an appropriate
monetary policy."
</P>
<P>
The problem was that Europe lacked the economic policy
coordination and had 14 separate currencies, he said. So he
insisted that EMU must not be seen as an optional extra.
</P>
<P>
"It is the necessary counterpart to the increasingly integrated
European economy, in which national policies lose much of their
force if exercised alone," Flynn stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
