<HEADLINE> China in Festive Mood as Congress Opens  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Comrade Jiang's report has established the leading position of
Deng Xiaoping Theory, and we have had a more clear understanding
of the next step of the reform," said Li Yinrong, a local
businessman.
</P>
<P>
Local residents in the city of Wenzhou in east China's Zhejiang
Province, paid utmost attention to Jiang's expositions on the
diverse sectors of economy.
</P>
<P>
"It gives the go-ahead to the growth of the varied economic
sectors and affirmed our efforts to promote these sectors of
economy over the past dozen years," said Xu Guanju, vice-president
of the Zhejiang Provincial Industrial and Commercial Federation,
adding that Wenzhou has drawn nationwide attention for its booming
diversified businesses.
</P>
<P>
This morning in Hohhot, capital of north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, local residents and tourists flocked to the
Xinhua Square to watch the live telecasting on huge TV screens.
</P>
<P>
"Comrade Jiang Zemin's report is really encouraging," Baoyin, a
herdsman of Mongol ethnic group, said in broken Han language.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the congress also has aroused strong response in
the outlying, less developed areas.
</P>
<P>
"We fully support the Party's policies," said Liu Changlin, a
village head in Chang'an Town, Fujin City of the northernmost
Heilongjiang Province. He told Xinhua that his villagers are among
the 30 million former poor rural people, mentioned by Comrade
Jiang in his report, who have overcome poverty in the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
After hearing Jiang's speech, officials from industrial bases
like northeast China's Shenyang city and east China's Nanjing felt
much relieved, as they are convinced that the congress will call
for a new round of the restructuring of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"I hold that after the Party Congress, there will a still
better external environment for state-owned firms to reform and
develop," said Zhang Shenghua, deputy Party secretary of the
Nanjing-based Panda Group, a renowned electronics giant in east
China. 
</P>
