<HEADLINE> Greek, Albanian Foreign Ministers Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister
Theodoros Pangalos today held talks with his visiting Albanian
counterpart, Paskal Milo, on ways of expanding cooperation between
the two Balkan countries.
</P>
<P>
They also talked about a European prospect for Albania, the
Balkan summit in Crete in early November and problems in the
Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the one-hour talks, the two men
described their talks as "the most favorable development in
Greek-Albanian relations in recent times," with Pangalos adding
that relations with Tirana were developing "in a most favorable
manner."
</P>
<P>
Pangalos said that a friendship and cooperation agreement
between the two countries would be ratified by the Greek
Parliament by March next year.
</P>
<P>
He also announced a series of measures and initiatives that
would further strengthen ties between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Greek President Costis Stephanopoulos had invited his Albanian
counterpart to visit Athens in early 1998, he said, adding that
the planned visit by Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis to
Albania next month was in the context of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Greece today presented Albania with 2 billion drachmas (about
7.14 million U.S. dollars) as urgent economic aid for the
neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos handed the money to Milo after their talks today.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that expert committees of both countries would be
meeting soon to thrash out the details of 18 million drachmas
(about 64,285 U.S. dollars) worth of Greek loans promised to
Albania to aid in the implementation of public works projects in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Milo, who arrived here Thursday for a three-day official visit
to Greece, also met with President Stephanopoulos and Prime
Minister Simitis earlier today.
</P>
<P>
He urged Albanians living in Greece to abide by Greek law and
invited Greek investors who had fled Albania in the wake of the
unrest to go back to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
