<HEADLINE> Qatar Launches Diplomatic Drive For Doha Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Qatar today launches a
diplomatic drive by sending a senior official to some Arab
countries to drum up support for the Middle East and North Africa
Economic Summit scheduled to be held in Doha in November.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of State For Foreign Affairs Ahmmed Ibin Abdullah
al Mahmoud left Doha today on an official visit to Algeria as part
of this diplomatic move which is also include visits to to some
other Arab states, the Qatari news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Algeria is the first leg of his five-state tour which will
also take him to Mauritania, Sudan, Djibouti and Yemen, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The tour comes a week before an Arab League's meeting on
the fourth Middle East and North Africa Economic Summit which
was strongly opposed by some Arab states due to an expected
Israeli participation.
</P>
<P>
In protest against the deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace
process, Syria, Lebanon, the Palestinian Authority, the UAE and
Saudi Arabia have decided to boycott the summit.
</P>
<P>
However, most of other Arab states adopt a wait-and-see
stand and await a final decision by the Arab League at the
meeting in Cairo on September 20 to 21.
</P>
<P>
Qatar remained determined to host the summit as scheduled
on November 16 to 18 despite the pressures. Qatari officials
said earlier this week that it is going ahead with
preparations for the summit and invitations would be sent out
at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The previous three conferences were held in Casablanca, Amman
and Cairo and attended by Arab states, Israel and their major
trade partners in the industrialized world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
