<HEADLINE> Jordanian PM Calls for Arab Solidarity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdul-Salam El-Majali urged the Arab states to put aside their
differences and work to ensure solidarity among them for the
benefit of their peoples.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference today at the end of his three-day state
visit to Sudan, El-Majali warned that "there are some quarters that
exploit the differences among the Arabs to destroy them."
</P>
<P>
He called on Arabs to shelve their differences for at least
five years during which cooperative relations should be developed
among them.
</P>
<P>
El-Majali made his trip to Arab states including Bahrain,
Qatar, Oman, Yemen, Egypt and Sudan, in a bid to revive the Arab
solidarity.
</P>
<P>
During his visit here, the Sudanese and the Jordanian sides
issued a joint communique underlining the necessity of cooperation
and they formed an ad hoc committee of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Jordan said its backs Sudan and supports the Khartoum peace
accord that was signed by the Sudanese government and six rebel
factions from South Sudan last April.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reviewed the situation in the Arab region and the
latest developments in the Arab-Israeli peace process. They voiced
concern over the dangers threatening the peace process, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides underscored the necessity of establishing just,
comprehensive and lasting peace in the region under the
resolutions of the U.N. Security Council and General Assembly to
ensure the return Arab legitimate rights.
</P>
<P>
They also highlighted the importance of the principles and
references on which the Middle East peace process was based and
the necessity of full implementation of what had been agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Jordan expressed deep concern over the sufferings of
the Iraqi and Libyan peoples due to the unjust embargoes. They
urged lifting of the sanctions imposed on the two peoples and
stopping the mass-sanction policy.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian delegation left here for home this afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
