<HEADLINE> Anti-Government Demonstrations Continue in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's conservative
Islamists today continued their so-called Friday demonstrations
to protest the newly adopted eight-year compulsory education
law, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
Around 1,000 protesters gathered outside the Beyazit Mosque
in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey, following their Friday
prayer services, shouting anti-government slogans.
</P>
<P>
They demanded the revision of the education law which was
adopted in the Parliament last month and the continuous
operation of religious schools.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators clashed with security police who tried to
block the parade, causing injuries on both sides.
</P>
<P>
In the capital city of Ankara, a group of conservative
Islamists staged a demonstration near the Bayrampasa
Mosque. Police detained 13 people, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrations have taken place every Friday after Muslim
prayer services since the education law took effect last month.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry has warned that those people staging
Friday demonstrations against the new education law will face
arrests and other punishment.
</P>
<P>
The education program launched by the Turkish government with
the support of the military is aimed at curbing the rapidly
growing fundamentalism in the secular Muslim country.
</P>
<P>
The law demands that students finish eight years of compulsory
education before they are permitted to start religious study,
leading to the closure of many religious schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
