<HEADLINE> UK's Enterprise Oil Tries to Meet Production Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Enterprise Oil, the UK's
largest independent explorer, tries to meet its ambitious
production targets despite lower output and few new discoveries in
the first half of 1997, according to The Financial Times today.
</P>
<P>
The company aims to produce an average of 320,000 barrels of
oil equivalent per day in 1999, up from 229,935 in the six months
to June 30.
</P>
<P>
Analysts estimate exploration discoveries, mainly from the Gulf
of Mexico, are about 20 million barrels so far this year, out of a
total of 80-100 million that might be expected for the full year.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Andrew Shilston, finance director, as saying,
"Investment would be higher in the second half as several large
projects got under way."
</P>
<P>
Development of Jotun, in which Enterprise holds 42.5 percent,
will cost about 240 million pounds (384 million US dollars) over
two years, making it the company's biggest single capital
investment commitment after Nelson in the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
Capital expenditure for the full year was put at 520 million
pounds (832 million US dollars), after a total of 180 million
pounds (288 million US dollars) in the first half.
</P>
<P>
Shilston said, "What we have been doing is something like
laying down vintages to drink in 10 years' time."
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted production had been lower than expected
owing to maintenance problems in the North Sea that had been
resolved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
