<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Literacy Standards Lag Far Behind Industrial Rivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain ranks second from the
bottom in a league table of literacy covering eight industrialized
countries, according to an international survey published today by
the Office for National Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The survey, based on a random sample of 3,800 British people
aged 16 to 65, found that more British adults are struggling at
the lowest literacy level than their counterparts in any other
developed country surveyed, except Poland.
</P>
<P>
It revealed that 22 percent, equivalent to around 8.4 million
in the population as a whole, could not make an accurate
comparison of two pieces of written information or work out simple
sums.
</P>
<P>
More than half the British population had literacy skills below
the standard generally agreed as the minimum necessary to cope
with the demands of modern life.
</P>
<P>
The survey also confirmed past findings that literacy skills
were poorer among those with lower levels of education and among
people who were out of work or in lower-skilled occupations.
</P>
<P>
Across the age ranges, those over 45 were more likely to have
worse literacy standards than the younger groups but there was
little difference between those aged 16-45, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
David Blunkett, the education and employment secretary, said
the results showed "there has been an unacceptable neglect of
literacy standards for too long." He also promised a white paper
on lifelong learning before the end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
