<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solana Reassures NATO Support for Bosnian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 12 (Xinhua) -- NATO chief Javier Solana
today reassured the international community and the Bosnians that
the Stabilization Force (SFOR) is fully ready to ensure a
problem-free municipal election in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival on the eve of the elections, Solana told the press
that his presence in Sarajevo was to underscore NATO's support for
the elections which he described as an important milestone in
implementing the Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
A NATO press release quoted Solana as saying, "The SFOR is
fully ready to prevent any difficulties during the elections. The
SFOR also stands ready to take firm action against the media whose
output is in persistent and blatant contradiction of either the
spirit or the letter of the Dayton peace agreement."
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief arrived in Bosnia after the alliance-led SFOR
was reinforced with more troops and equipped with more F-16
fighter jets and policing tools such as batons, shields, tear
gases and non-lethal grenades.
</P>
<P>
Solana told the press that the SFOR had been temporarily
reinforced by six battalions and the SFOR strength now stood at
nearly 40,000.
</P>
<P>
"These soldiers will ensure that the municipal elections are
held in a secure environment," the NATO chief said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,500 international observers are also in
Bosnia-Herzegovina to oversee the two-day elections to be held in
the 16 municipalities in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that Bosnian Croats had dropped their
threat to boycott the elections. In the past two weeks, both the
Bosnian Croats, led by the HDZ, and the Bosnian Serbs under the
leadership of the Pale-based SDS had been threatening to stay
away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
