<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Backs Debt Reduction for Bolivia under HIPC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) --The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) today announced its support for the
international debt-reduction for Bolivia in the framework of
assisting heavily indebted poor countries (HIPC).
</P>
<P>
The Bank's Committee of the Board of Governors, meeting here
this week endorsed a decision of its Board of Executive Directors
to participate in the reduction of Bolivia's debt to ensure debt
sustainability at a 225 percent debt-to-export ratio.
</P>
<P>
The IDB will provide relief in the amount of 155 million U.S.
dollars in present value, or about 260 million dollars in nominal
terms, equivalent to almost 35 percent of the relief to be
provided by all of Bolivia's creditors and more than one half of
the amount for multilateral institutions.
</P>
<P>
The IDB's portion is nearly three times greater than the
next-largest amount provided by a single institution.
</P>
<P>
IDB President Enrique V. Iglesias praised the "spirit of
solidarity" among the 46 member countries of the Bank in their
decision to join the initiative.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF), which
are jointly launched the HIPC initiative last year, also approved
debt relief for Bolivia earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Bolivia will become the first Latin American country to receive
debt relief under the HIPC program. It is expected to gain access
to the benefits of debt relief within a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
