<HEADLINE> Three Opposition Parties to Boycott Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of the three
major opposition political parties: the SDF, the NUDP and the CDU
have resolved to boycott the upcoming presidential elections
billed for October 12, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced at a press conference in Yaounde
this evening by the three opposition parties namely the Social
Democratic Front (SDF), the National Union for Democracy and
Progress (NUDP) and the Camerounian Democratic Union (CDU).
</P>
<P>
In a joint declaration signed by the SDF' s chairman John Fru
Ndi, the NUDP's vice chairman Celestin Bedzigui and the CDU's
chairman Adamou Ndam Njoya, the three parties said they will not
take part in any elections under the country's present conditions
because they thought "no free and fair elections can be held in
Cameroun in the present context."
</P>
<P>
They are especially not satisfied with the just ended extra
ordinary session of the National Assembly where, they said, all
attempts by the opposition to introduce even the slightest
amendments to the law governing the presidential elections were
swept aside by the parliamentarians of the ruling party Cameroun
People's Democratic Movement who enjoys an absolute majority in
the house.
</P>
<P>
They insist on "no good laws, no elections." 
</P>
