<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Open Discussions in Party Congress Attract Overseas Press (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To open the discussion to overseas press means that the Chinese
Communist Party is building a more efficient democratic political
system with more open and transparent politics, he said.
</P>
<P>
Although there are regulations to prevent reporters from
interviewing congress delegates during the discussion, some
reporters cannot help breaking the rules.
</P>
<P>
Wang Chuanli, professor of the China University of Political
Science and Law, sat close to the reporters, which made it easy
for some Hong Kong and Macao reporters standing close to her to
ask her lots of questions. Ms. Wang answered each of them briefly
for politeness.
</P>
<P>
Among the overseas reporters, some are China hands based in
Beijing. And some others are sent by their news organizations to
cover the congress. But many of them speak fluent Chinese. So they
talked with the Chinese reporters in Chinese Putonghua.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Ptashkin, a Russian reporter from Trud, a daily
newspaper, told Xinhua in standard Chinese that he wants to give
an objective description of China's reforms and opening-up and
compare China with Russia in economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
China has made important strides in opening-up, and the opening
of the panel discussion in the current Party congress is an
important symbol of China's all-round opening-up, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I have no reporting mission today, but only to gain insights
of the 15th Party congress," said Hugo Restall, editorial page
writer from Asian Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
The discussion of Shanghai delegation was just as attractive as
that of Beijing delegation. The only difference was the discussion
by Shanghai delegation started 15 minutes earlier at the request
of 100-plus Chinese and overseas reporters.
</P>
<P>
Speakers from the Shanghai delegation ranged from Shanghai
mayors to bank president, chairman of the board of directors. A
Hong Kong reporter commented the panel discussion by Shanghai
delegates was fairly informative and transparent. The speech by
Shanghai mayor quoted 50 latest figures to support his points, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The positive response from the overseas press was an annotation
for a talk by Wang Zheren, director of the 15th Party Congress
Press Center: "To open panel discussions is to give the press an
opportunity to know the conference proceeding and what's happening
in China."  
</P>
</TEXT>
