<HEADLINE> Open Discussions in Party Congress Attract Overseas Press (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua)-- Although there were still 30
minutes before the panel discussion began this afternoon, the
Beijing Conference Hall at the Great Hall of the People, venue of
the discussion for Beijing delegates, was packed with more than
100 Chinese and overseas reporters.
</P>
<P>
As there were only 46 seats reserved for the press, many
reporters remained standing out of the line separating delegates
from the press.
</P>
<P>
"Although it's tiring, we are closer to the congress delegates
and we can hear them more clearly," said an AFP reporter.
</P>
<P>
Mics, cassette recorders were seen piling before the
loudspeaker at the corner of the conference room. More than ten
video cameras and photo cameras were clicking in the conference
room.
</P>
<P>
According to conference regulations, the congress opened six
panel discussions today to overseas reporters. As it's the first
time to open such discussions to the overseas press, it is hailed
by the foreign press as an "unprecedented opening move".
</P>
<P>
The discussions of Shaanxi, Shandong, Inner Mongolia, Beijing,
Shanghai and Jiangsu delegations open today attracted the
attention of reporters from Hong Kong, Macao, Taiwan and the
foreign press, with those of Beijing and Shanghai catching the most
attention.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing is the capital city of China and there are many hot
spots," said a reporter from the Hong Kong Economic Guide.
</P>
<P>
The reporter attended the opening session of the congress
yesterday morning and rushed to the press conference given by
large state firms in the afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
