<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegate of China's Last Hunting Ethnic Group Shows up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- "I am the head of the
Autonomous Banner of Oroqen nationality, the last hunting ethnic
group in China," hardly had the stocky Meng Songlin begun to
introduce himself than all reporters rose to their feet and turned
their cameras at him.
</P>
<P>
A banner is an administrative division of county level.
</P>
<P>
"As descendant of a hunter, I feel excited that I could come to
Beijing as a delegate to the Party congress and listen to Comrade
Jiang Zemin's report," said the 42-year-old Meng in a panel
discussion in the Great Hall of the People today, which was open
for the first time to the journalists from Hong Kong, Macao and
Taiwan as well as foreign journalists covering the congress.
</P>
<P>
"He pointed out in his report that only the Party could lead
the Chinese people toward national independence and a happy life,"
said Meng. "I shall give my hearty agreement in this regard."
</P>
<P>
Before 1949, when the new China was founded, the Oroqen people
had lived as hunters in the primitive forests of Inner Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
"At that time, the Oroqen lived by hunting on horsebacks and
ate by campfire. My father was born on a hill slope, and I had
been living among hunters dressed in roe deer-skin clothings until
I went to primary school at 12," said Meng.
</P>
<P>
The Oroqen Autunomous Banner was founded in 1951. Seven years
later, all Oroqen settled down, thanks to money allocation from
the central government with which they built houses in their new
settlement. Its population so far has reached 2,031, compared with
a number of something over 700 in 1949.
</P>
<P>
"The founding of new China has brought prosperity to an ethnic
group once on the brink of extinction," said Meng.
</P>
<P>
Meng went on that the Oroqen is undergoing a transformation in
its mode of production. "We are now pursuing a broad variety of
production instead of solely hunting," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Meng, hunting can no longer provide an ample life
to his people.
</P>
<P>
"What's more, people in China and from abroad are calling for
protection of wildlife on which we live," added Meng. "That's why
we issued a ban on hunting in January of last year.
</P>
<P>
After two years of persuasion and explanation, the remaining
218 households, or 744 hunters, were finally talked into unloading
their hunting guns which they had carried all their life, and
joining others to take up farming tools.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Oroqen started a diversified economy with
farming as the main occupation.
</P>
<P>
In the Oroqen Autonomous Banner, which is half as large as
Zhejiang province, 85 farms have been set up. Annual income per
capita in the banner topped 1,736 yuan last year, approximately
600 yuan more than that prior to the ban on hunting was
implemented.
</P>
<P>
With aid from the government, every household in the banner now
has access to electricity power and has cable TVs fixed up. "Some
of the families even own telephones," Meng told the reporters.
"Moreover, the government offers tuition fees for all children
from primary schools through colleges."
</P>
<P>
Meng added that his banner would devote to non-pollution
industry for the benefit of ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
"Despite our population size, we do not want to be left the
poorest," he said, fully convinced that the Oroqen will strive to
become among the most wealthy in China under the guidance of the
great banner of Deng Xiaoping Theory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investors Show Rising Interest in Xiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investors have
exhibited their rising interest in investing in Xiamen in east
China's Fujian province, with agreements signed so far for 62
projects at the ongoing '97 China Investment and Trade Talks.
</P>
<P>
Su Shuili, vice-mayor of Xiamen, said at a press conference
held here today that the new agreements involve a total of 1.13
billion US dollars of investment, including more than one billion
US dollars of foreign funding.
</P>
<P>
"Of the projects, 30 each involve an investment of 10 million
US dollars or more, one even with 150 million US
dollars," Su said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 62 projects are related to the chemical,
electronics, power and machine-building industries. Su predicted
that some will require the most advanced technology and equipment,
which will promote the city's development.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan investors have signed 24 projects with companies in
Xiamen, covering agriculture, industry, tourism, real estate and
infrastructure construction. "This is the first time that Taiwan
investment has exceeded that from Hong Kong," added the official.
</P>
<P>
European and American businessmen also set their sights on
Xiamen's markets, signing eight agreements involving 127 million
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Su also said that a group of import-export contracts worth of
340 million US dollars has been signed during the ongoing talks, a
rise of 10.52 percent over last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
