<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rhee In-je Announces Bid for South Korean Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Rhee In-je, governor of Kyonggi
Province, formally declared Saturday that he would run on his own
the coming presidential election while bolting from the ruling New
Korea Party (NKP).
</P>
<P>
The 49-year-old governor also vowed to bring young politicians
to the fore in politics as the first step to advance a "revolution
in politics" if elected.
</P>
<P>
Rhee's unexpected bid for the presidency is expected to affect
greatly the ongoing four-side presidential race, which seemed to
be heading toward a showdown between the NKP and the main
opposition National Congress for New Politics (NCNP).
</P>
<P>
The ruling party fears Rhee's decision will split its candidate
Lee Hoi-chang's vote and ultimately help the front-runner,
opposition NCNP's Kim Dae-jung win the election.
</P>
<P>
The latest opinion polls show Rhee and Lee are behind Kim, who
is in the fourth bid for the presidency at his 70s.
</P>
<P>
The NKP's high officials said President Kim Young-sam expressed
disappointment at Rhee's decision, but party sources say only a
few party members will follow Rhee, given that party lawmakers of
Rhee's supporters opposed his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
Rhee's jump into the presidential race slated for December 18
had been forecast since his resignation from the governorship last
Monday, which was a precondition for the candidacy.
</P>
<P>
Rhee lost the ruling party's presidential candidacy to Chairman
Lee Hoi-chang in the party's nomination contest in July.
</P>
<P>
But Rhee's continued high popularity and candidate Lee's
unexpectedly weak show in the early stages of the presidential
race made it difficult for the loser to give up his presidential
ambition.
</P>
<P>
Born in Nonsan, South Chungchong Province, Rhee was a two-term
lawmaker until being elected governor of the populous province in
local elections in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer-turned politician, a close associate of President
Kim, served as the first Labor Minister under the Kim Young-sam
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
