<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opposes Random Adjustments to UN Assessment Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Any revision or
adjustment to the UN assessment rates should be based on the
principle of ability to pay, a Chinese representative to the
United Nations said today.
</P>
<P>
The representative, who asked not to be identified, made the
remark in a response to reports that the United States had asked
China to increase its UN assessment rates to more than 4 percent,
and China was considering the U.S. proposal.
</P>
<P>
The representative said China did not object to making
appropriate revision or adjustment to the UN assessment rates, but
any revision or adjustment should be based on the principle of
ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China would not accept any proposal that went
against this principle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
