<HEADLINE> Russian Oil Industry Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia gained a 0.7-percent
increase in oil output in the first eight months of 1997, Russian
First Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov said today.
</P>
<P>
At an oil industry meeting, Nemtsov, who is visiting the
Khanty-Mansiisk ethnic autonomous region of Siberia, said that
three large oil companies -- LUKoil, Surgutneftegas and Rosneft --
have the incremental output.
</P>
<P>
He said the government should pursue partnerships with oil
companies, which contribute 20 percent of taxes to the federal
budgetary revenue and heed the interests of the state and the
companies.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the government would soon discuss the issue
of car import tax duties.
</P>
<P>
First Deputy Minister for Fuel and Energy Viktor Ott said that
Russia's oil and gas output in the January-August period of this
year has reached 203 million metric tons, or 3.8 million tons,
higher than expected.
</P>
<P>
However, Ott said Russia's oil industry remains to have
difficulties with one in every three refineries working at a loss
and the number of idle oil wells accounting for 25 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
He cited a serious decline in this year's pace of oil
extraction, saying about 55 percent of the country's oil fields so
far have been difficult to pump.
</P>
<P>
The highest oil output is in the Tyumen region, Siberia. It
accounts for more than 43 percent of the total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
