<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Takes Measures to Ease Traffic Jams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital needs
more subways, belt highways and special bus lanes on city streets
to deal with its grim traffic situation, Beijing's Assistant Mayor
Zhen Yijun has said here recently.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's road network is overloaded by more than one
million motor vehicles -- a number that increases by about 15
percent a year, Zhen said.
</P>
<P>
Traffic studies show that during peak traffic times, the
average speed of vehicles on main roads in the urban areas is
below 20 kilometers an hour.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the city has only 544 public parking lots which can
accommodate 32,000 cars. He said the city needs more parking lots
with an accommodating capacity of at least 50,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
To ease road congestion, Beijing is speeding up construction of
some key transport facilities, he said.
</P>
<P>
The subway from Fuxingmen to Bawangfen, currently under
construction, is expected to be put into use in 1999. Preparations
are being made for the construction of the No. 5 subway from
Songjiazhuang in the south to Beiyuan in the north and the Xiyi
subway from Xizhimen to the Summer Palace.
</P>
<P>
Beijing expects to re-distribute 70 to 80 percent of its
traffic volume to underground.
</P>
<P>
A 65-km belt highway, the fourth one in Beijing, will be built
by stages and three traffic lanes for special buses are to be
opened this year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is planning to control the amount of motor vehicles to
reduce the pressure on its road network, according to Zhen.
</P>
<P>
Traffic control is to be aided by modern technology;
closed-circuit TV monitoring systems will soon be installed to
regulate two belt highways, he added.
</P>
<P>
Traffic jams decreased in Beijing after the city took some
traffic control measures. The congestion in 15 of the 99 seriously
blocked sections has been eased.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
