<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diverse Forms of Public Ownership to Promote Economic Growth, Li Peng (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Concerning the issue of joint stock partnership, Li Peng said
China should manage well state-owned large enterprises while
adopting a flexible policy toward small ones. There are many
methods to deal with small enterprises in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Experience accumulated in these years shows the introduction of
joint stock partnership is an effective way, Li said. In most
cases, workers in enterprises which practice joint stock
partnership buy stock to share risks of the enterprises, and
therefore have stronger sense of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, by issuing shares the enterprises will have
more funds, with which they can repay their loans and finally
extricate themselves from the burden of repaying interests.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Li said, the enterprises could carry on
technological transformation and development with the funds so
that their staying power would be further strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Through the introduction of such partnership, quite a few
enterprises have reduced losses and increased profits. Management
in these enterprises have been improved as well, Li noted.
</P>
<P>
To sum up, the joint stock partnership has been proved through
practice to be an effective way of managing well large enterprises
and adopting a flexible policy toward small ones, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng also called for down-to-earth work in carrying out the
partnership, saying that the criterion for judging the success is
"three favorables" -- favorable to promoting the growth of the
productive forces in a socialist society, increasing the overall
strength of the socialist state and raising the people's living
standards.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that everything should be done in accordance with
reality. Hasty and arbitrary quotas should be avoided, he added.
Work in this regard should be done according to the law of the
market economy, and be gradually standardized.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng said that banking is playing an increasingly important
role in the national economy. Financial reform should be carried
out in accordance with the reality of the country. The economic
structure should be further adjusted through reform. A prudent
attitude should be adopted toward the opening of the capital
market.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng said that China should draw a lesson from the financial
crises that took place in Mexico and recently in southeast Asian
countries. The quality of financial capital should be improved,
financial supervision and management intensified, financial crisis
prevented and financial reform accelerated, He said.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng pointed out that the private sector of the economy
plays an important role in many areas, especially in the
handicraft and retail trades.
</P>
<P>
He said the private sector has provided a large number of job
opportunities and has more rooms to develop in the service trade.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng expressed his belief that diversified forms of public
ownership will surely help consolidate and develop the public
sector of the economy, thus promoting China's all-round economic
growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finance Ministers Meet to Discuss Taxation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONDORF LES BAINS, Luxembourg, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The EU
finance ministers today started discussion on a global approach to
taxation as a run-up to the convergence for the European single
currency.
</P>
<P>
The informal meeting was the first opportunity since April last
year for the finance ministers to develop cooperation at EU level
on taxation policy and on measures to curtail harmful tax
competition in the single market.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held at the Luxembourg town on the border with
France, was presided over by the Luxembourg presidency, which has
made taxation one of its two main priorities during its six-month
tenure.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers last met in April 1996 at Verona, Italy,
and a consensus has emerged since then on the key challenges to
taxation policies in the 15-nation union.
</P>
<P>
They felt there was an urgent need to implement concrete
measures to combat harmful tax competition and agreed that such an
approach was the most promising route to follow.
</P>
<P>
Though EU-level decision is not expected, the informal meeting
will delve into discussions on general policy orientations by
demonstrating their respective initial reactions and their
individual components.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive agency of the union,
will come forward with a more developed taxation package as the
basis on which the ministers will seek significant progress at
their formal meeting in December this year.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed that globalization presents new
opportunities for national economies but blows up the risks of
harmful tax competition.
</P>
<P>
Electronic commerce, which makes the physical location of
activities much less significant, may increase the potential
impact of tax differentials on business decisions and may
aggravate the risk of harmful tax competition, tax avoidance and
tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
Tax competition is an important factor in the shift in the tax
burden to the less mobile tax base of labor. Given the
considerable differences in mobility between different sectors of
the labor market, the trend is for the burden of taxation to shift
increasingly to the least skilled and less mobile employees.
</P>
<P>
Highly skilled employees and professionals are increasingly
mobile and responsive to tax differentials.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will also deal with the topic of the exchange
rates for the single currency which is to be launched on January
1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to examine the scope for defining criteria
for fixing exchange rates for currencies participating in the
final stage of the economic and monetary union (EMU) in relation
to the future single currency.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty, signed in 1992, proposed that the
European Council should set up an exchange rate system between the
euro and non-EU currencies, and make general recommendations for
an exchange rate policy between the single currency and non-EU
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Yves-Thibault de Silguy, European commissioner in charge of
economic and monetary affairs, is expected to encourage member
states at the meeting to work out their respective measures for
the run-up to the inauguration of the single currency.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, Belgium, Luxembourg, Ireland, Finland, Italy and
the Netherlands have worked out such national programs for
changing over to the euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
