Deputy Foreign Minister Rafat Mahdi, whose mission was to
coordinate efforts for the coming Tehran summit in December of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
Iran and Pakistan pledged support to the warring factions in
Afghanistan. Iran suffered a big blow when Kabul fell last
September into the hands of Taliban militia, which Tehran accused
was armed and supported by Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Taliban has already controlled about 90 percent of the
territory of Afghanistan. Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani, who
was supported by Tehran, fled before Taliban's advance into the
capital.
</P>
<P>
During today's talks, Kharrazi termed the trend of
Tehran-Islamabad ties as "good" and called for further exchange
of views and experiences in an effort to explore fresh avenues for
further expansion of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mahdi said here today that Iran had always been
sensitive to regional developments and played a positive and
effective role in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif visited Tehran in June
but failed to reach agreement with the Iranian side on a
settlement of the Afghan crisis. 
