<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Maintains Stable Public Security Order (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The police force's efficiency has also been upgraded, thanks to
the establishment of the police alarm systems covering the whole
province and nearby sea areas, which were the first of the kind
set up in China.
</P>
<P>
Various training courses have been held for the police,
covering practices to be followed during emergencies. The ratio of
police who have received college-level education has risen from
13.9 percent to 30 percent, ranking first in the country.
</P>
<P>
With the reinforcing of the police force and the improvement of
their facilities, great progress has been scored in the public
security field in Hainan over recent years. The number of fights
involving weapons has also been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
Theft of latex from rubber trees, used to make rubber products,
had been a major annoyance for the island's farmers, with over
1,400 cases occurring each year. The number has dropped to dozens
each year since 1995, and the production of rubber has reached the
record in history.
</P>
<P>
The gun-related cases has also dropped significantly.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the public security bureaus have solved more than
15,000 criminal cases involving pornography and gambling since the
establishment of the special economic zone.
</P>
<P>
There have been no bank robberies in the province since April
1995, whereas before then, bank heists were all-too-common on
Hainan. Meanwhile, no serious criminal cases have occurred its
rural areas, which make up 80 percent of the island's total area.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Postal Rates to Be Reduced in Zambia's Rural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Postal Services
intends to reduce postal rates in rural areas to enable the rural
community to communicate.
</P>
<P>
Public Relations Manager Francis Mumba said the plan, which
has been endorsed by the board has reached an advanced stage and
will be implemented soon.
</P>
<P>
He said after critically examining the problems facing the
people in rural areas the corporation has decided to reduce its
rates in order to accommodate them.
</P>
<P>
Mumba said because of the high rates people in rural areas
have stopped writing letters.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the current general decline of the economy in the
country which has forced many people to choose between letter
writing or buying food, many opt for the latter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mumba said as part of the diversification program the postal
services, in conjunction with the state lottery of Zambia, will
start selling Pick-A-Ticket at its offices in some parts of the
country from next week.
</P>
<P>
he said since the corporation has the largest retail outlets
in the country, Zambia Postal Services has entered into an
agreement with the state lottery to sell its Pick-A-Ticket at a
commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
