<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Visits Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President
Fidel Ramos arrived here today for a two-day visit and received a
red-carpet welcome accorded by Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmed
al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that a Philippine president visits
Kuwait. During his stay here, Ramos is expected to hold talks with
Kuwaiti leaders to on ways of promoting bilateral relations, and
on regional and international issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will sign an agreement on cultural
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The visit of Ramos, who is accompanied by a large group of
businessmen, is expected to strengthen bilateral ties and offer
opportunities of trade and investment for both sides, effectively
reversing the declining trend in bilateral trade over the past
years.
</P>
<P>
Last year, their trade volume slid to 34 million
U.S. dollars, with an annual decrease of 32 percent from 202.4
million dollars in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait hosts hundreds of thousands of Filipino laborers. The
Philippines announced Friday to lift a ban to allow the processing
of "qualified workers applying as household workers" for Kuwait
and Saudi Arabia, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos will meet with the Filipino community at a downtown
hotel on the eve of his departure for Prague, the Czech Republic
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' visit to Kuwait fulfills his economic mission to all
the six states of the Gulf Cooperation Council, whose other
members are Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Bahrain
and Oman, and concludes cooperation agreements in culture and
tourism with them.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who is on a four-nation tour, had just ended his visit
to Russia and will continue his trip to the Czech Republic and
Austria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Aid Worker Kidnapped in Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 13 (Xinhua) -- A local aid worker for an
international organization has been abducted by unidentified
gunmen in south Mogadishu on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The aid worker, Idiris Mohaqmed Osman, head of the World Food
Program (WFP) office in Mogadishu, was surrounded by five to six
armed men driving a land cruiser as he walked out of a Muse Boqor
Mosque after his Friday prayers.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitness said the gunmen have ordered Osman to enter the
land cruiser before driving him away to an unknown destination
without hurting him. The reason for the kidnap is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
However, friends of the abducted aid worker told reporters
that they heard previous job and contract quarrels between Osman
and other Somalis who are suspected to have masterminded the
kidnap.
</P>
<P>
So far, the fate of Osman is not known and there has no
demands yet made by the abductors despite the continuation of
mediation efforts for his safe release.
</P>
<P>
The kidnap took place only two days after South Mogadishu
faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid met with a high-level
delegation from the United Nations agencies serving in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The delegation led by Dominick Langen Bacher, head of United
Nations Development Program (UNDP) who is in charge of all U.N.
agencies operating in Somalia, discussed with Hussein Aidid about
the humanitarian situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the headquarters of Hussein Aidid said the
meeting mainly focused on relief operations and the security of
aid workers.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. delegation also met with the North Mogadishu faction
leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed, at the natural port of El-Ma'an, 30 km
north of the city for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Somali aid worker serving the French aid agency
Action Contra Le Faime (ACF), was released late Friday night in
North Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The aid worker, Sheikh Omar Aw-dhegle, was released unhurt
after serious efforts were exerted by elders and intellectuals in
the area. Aw-dhegle was abducted by Somali gunmen on Thursday. No
ransom was paid for his release, according to friends close to
Aw-dhegle.
</P>
<P>
The security situation in both sides of the war-torn capital
has deteriorated in the past few weeks as free-lance gunmen are
carrying out actions of killing, looting and abduction of
civilians for mainly fortune-seeking purposes.
</P>
<P>
Faction leaders have warned that all such gunmen will be dealt
with accordingly, but so far no concrete measures have been
taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Warns Against Nigeria Business Scam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese Foreign Ministry
today warned of a scam which has extracted 5 billion U.S. dollars
from unsuspecting victims worldwide.
</P>
<P>
An influx of faxes from Nigeria to Lebanese businessmen
promising easy money prompted the ministry advisory, Beirut's
newspaper the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that the faxes or letters have arrived
marked "urgent and confidential," many on letterheads bearing the
insignia of the "Government of Nigeria," asking for assistance in
circumventing Nigeria's tight foreign exchange laws by
transferring money using foreign accounts.
</P>
<P>
If the recipient accepts, he or she is asked for an account
number, as well as "advance fees, transfer taxes or performance
bonds."
</P>
<P>
After the initial payment, the Foreign Ministry said,
complications arise and the Nigerian party normally requests more
money.
</P>
<P>
Several Lebanese have been asked "to transfer money again and
again until the sum reached 500,000 U.S. dollars," the ministry
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
