<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIS Countries to Enhance Cooperation on Curbing Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) member countries have signed a series of
documents on cooperation in fighting organized crime.
</P>
<P>
The documents were signed at the fifth meeting of the CIS
Interior Ministerial Committee, which concluded Friday in Baku,
capital of Azerbaijan, Itar-Tass news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Under the documents, the 12 CIS interior ministers pledged to
improve the organizational set-up, equipment and information
back-up of the committee's Coordination Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed the possibility of setting up an
INTERPOL sub-branch in the CIS region.
</P>
<P>
It was decided at the meeting to establish a unified
trans-national crime-cracking mechanism to implement the accord on
cooperation in punishing criminals.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Premier and Interior Minister Anatoly Kulikov
said before the meeting that the committee had coordinated well in
fighting organized crimes, but further cooperation is necessary to
make its work more effective. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranians Jubilant Over 4-2 Victory over China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of shopkeepers who
watched their TV screens at downtown rose to scream and jump in
the air as Iranian soccer team scored its last goal in a 4-2
victory over China in a World Cup Asian zone qualifier in the
Chinese port city of Dalian today.
</P>
<P>
"We are very happy. This will surely pave the way for our team
to advance to the 1998 World Cup finals in France," said a textile
shop owner named Mostafa Dadkhah.
</P>
<P>
He told about 20 other shopkeepers to be his guest, and ordered
ice cream and soda to celebrate Iran's come-from-behind victory
over China.
</P>
<P>
Iran, who played the away game in group a, trailed 1-0 in the
first half and conceded the second goal one minute after the
break. But the Iranians soared back devastatingly, blasting four
goals in a row to seal a brilliant victory.
</P>
<P>
Aside from celebration and the jubilant mood, most Iranians
believed that despite a passive first half, the Iranian team was
able to turn the tide in the second.
</P>
<P>
"In the first half we thought that our team was not in good
form, but by the end of the game, when we saw how tired the
Chinese were, we realized that our strategy was to make the
Chinese tired first, so we could create chances to beat them in
the second half," a university student Ja'far Baqeri said.
</P>
<P>
Another Iranian sport fan said that although before this game
he did not think high of the Iranian head coach Mohammad Mayelee
Kohan, but now he believes that the man can lead Iran to gain
bigger victories.
</P>
<P>
Rahim Rezabeik, a construction engineer, said:"Mr. Kohan showed
 that he was an excellent coach. He sent up Ali Modier-Rousta to
the field at the right time, and his decision of pulling out
Khodadad Azizi in the second half proved a wise move."
</P>
<P>
Most Iranians interviewed after the game said that the Chinese
made mistakes by just following Iran's star strikers such as Ali
Dayee, Azizi and Karim Baqeri, but forgetting other players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Says Albright's Efforts Encouraging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the regional Doha Economic Summit scheduled for November,
Mubarak said Egypt's participation hinges on progress made on the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
A number of Arab countries have threatened to boycott the
conference in protest against Israeli hardline Mideast policy
which has been blamed for the stalemate of the peace process. And
the U.S., a strong advocate of the regional economic cooperation
forum, however, insists that it should go as planned.
</P>
<P>
Albright stressed the conference would be a chance for the
Mideast to be part of global economy and a favor for all people in
the region. "It is valuable in its own rights," she added.
</P>
<P>
Today's talks were also attended by Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa, Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, Mubarak's Political
Advisor Osama el-Baz as well as U.S. Mideast Peace Coordinator
Dennis Ross and U.S. Ambassador Edward Walker.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived here late last night, held a session of
talks with Moussa at breakfast this morning before seeing Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
After three days of talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and PNA President Yasser Arafat, Albright admitted
failure to break the confidence crisis between them, saying she
would not come back to "tread water" in the near future until
"they made hard decisions."
</P>
<P>
In what she called small steps towards a resumption of the
peace talks, the U.S. and the Palestinians have agreed to set up a
joint committee to monitor the PNA's efforts to combat terrorism,
according to Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
Albright said earlier, Israeli and Palestinian diplomats will
meet in Washington and New York in the coming two weeks in a bid
to revive the peace process that came to a halt in March after
Israel began to build new homes for Jews in East Jerusalem the
Palestinians claimed as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian officials said on condition of anonymity that Ross
will return to the region in the coming weeks to follow up
Albright's visit.
</P>
<P>
The peace crisis worsened after a wave of suicide bombings hit
Jerusalem in the past five weeks, killing more than 20 people and
wounding over 300. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
