<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cooperative Medical Service Resumed in Rural Hainan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Cooperative medical service
has made a comeback in the countryside of the island province of
Hainan, so far covering 30 percent of its rural
population.
</P>
<P>
The system was first introduced onto the island, located at the
southernmost tip of China, in the 1970s, but was suspended in the
late 1980s. With the vigorous support of the Chinese government in
recent years, Hainan farmers are once again joining in cooperative
medical service.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, cooperative medical service was
established in 76 villages across the province benefiting more
than 100,000 local residents.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, every participant pays an amount of between
10 and 40 yuan (1.2 to 4.8 US dollars) annually to the village or
township medical fund, which is also subsidized by local
governments. Then, the medical fund will reimburse 30-50 percent
of his or her medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
Cooperative medical service, based on individual as well as
public funding and voluntary participation, is regarded as the
most reasonable and effective way of ensuring adequate medical
care for farmers, said Lu Qing, director of the Provincial Health
Department.
</P>
<P>
He added that Hainan aims to have 85 percent of its rural
population covered by cooperative medical service by 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, France to Work Together on International Front </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rome, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Italy and France intend to work
together on all leading international issues, Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini said Friday after his talks with French
Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint press conference, both Dini and Vedrine
accentuated the positive factors in bilateral relations and their
common intention to pursue "concrete actions" on European and
international problems.
</P>
<P>
Dini also announced that in addition to signing the new
European Union (EU) Treaty in October in Amsterdam, capital of the
Netherlands, Italy, France and Belgium will present a joint
statement urging their EU partners to tackle problems involving
institutional reforms that were left out of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that Italy will be among the first group of EU
members adopting the euro, the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
Both sides shared a strong consensus on the Middle
East. Vedrine said the peace process had run into a "dead end" and
Dini showed the same disappointment over the stalemate of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Europe's future, the two stressed the need to
reinforce the Union on an institutional level and to introduce a
common foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Their discussion on other international issues, Dini told
reporters, centered on the reconstruction of Albania and Bosnia.
</P>
</TEXT>
