<HEADLINE> Mali's Premier Steps Down to Solve Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Mali's cabinet headed by
Premier Ibrahim Boubacar Keita have resigned in an attempt to
solve a political crisis resulted from the second multi-party
national elections this year.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today from Bamako, capital of Mali said,
the news was made known by President Alpha Oumar Konare Friday
when he was meeting with the country's political parties.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting were representatives of the Opposition
Alliance comprising 18 parties, which boycotted this year's
presidential and parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
Keita is chairman of Konare's Alliance for Democracy in Mali
(ADEMA) which emerged victorious in parliamentary elections in
July and August.
</P>
<P>
The crisis has been a blow to Mali's image as a model
democracy after a successful transition from dictatorship in
1992.
</P>
<P>
Konare has been trying to build up his bases for a coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties have demanded the premier's departure
as a prerequisite although their priority is given to fresh
elections besides setting free 10 opposition leaders who had been
under arrest since August 10.
</P>
<P>
The 10 who are accused of inciting violence and causing
unrest, have been held responsible for the death of a policeman
as unrest broke out at an opposition rally in Mali's capital of
Bamako.
</P>
<P>
Keita stepped down in June after Konare's re-election but was
named to lead a government until after the parliamentary
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
