<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Says Albright's Efforts Encouraging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALEXANDRIA, EGYPT, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak said here today the outcome of U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright's first peace-saving trip to the Mideast
is promising and encouraging.
</P>
<P>
Albright's trip gives hope to the peace process, Mubarak told
a press conference held after a two-hour meeting with her.
</P>
<P>
All the statements she made on the trip which started three
days ago and the announcements by the U.S. State Department are
"balancing, encouraging and promising," Mubarak told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"After that (her trip), I think the peace process will be
easier to pursue," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said he expects continuing discussions and
coordination among the Palestinians, Israelis and Americans to
move forward as far as possible the Mideast peace process until it
reaches a just and comprehensive settlement.
</P>
<P>
Albright, on her first trip to the region since taking office
in January, said she is encouraged by the willingness of the
leaders of the parties concerned to push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I was impressed by their yearning for peace...The Mideast is
sick of bombs," she said, before wrapping up the fourth leg of the
trip which has taken her to Israel, the Palestinian self-rule
areas and Syria.
</P>
<P>
She said it's high time for the people of the region to
concentrate on building dignity, security and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Asked on whether Israel's demand for security has been
overblown and the Palestinian security need ignored, the
secretary of state reiterated the importance of mutual
responsibility and commitment to peace.
</P>
<P>
"I made it clear that for peace to go forward, both sides have
to fulfill their mutual responsibility and obligation," she said,
adding that "terrorism should not dominate the scene of the
region."
</P>
<P>
While warning against any unilateral decisions that may
aggravate the situation, she urged Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) to exert 100 percent effort to combat terrorism, which is
"the enemy of peace, both for the Israelis and Palestinians."
</P>
<P>
Praising the enormous role in the Mideast by Egypt which she
called a "strategic partner," Albright said Cairo and Washington
have a share of mutual interest in curbing new threats to security
in the region and easing tensions should they occur.
</P>
<P>
Both Egypt and the U.S. believe a permanent settlement should
be a just and comprehensive peace for the Palestinians and
Israelis, in line with the Madrid, Oslo agreements and the
land-for-peace principle, she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
