<HEADLINE> Kipketer, Kumbernuss Win Overall IAAF Grand Prix Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Wilson Kipketer clinched the
1997 IAAF Grand Prix overall title after winning the 800 meters
at this year's final meet in Fukuoka on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
German Astrid Kumbernuss won the overall women's title after
capturing the shot put with a throw of 20.95 meters.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer, born in Kenya but representing his adopted nation
Denmark, easily took the men's 800 meters in one minute 42.98
seconds.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old also won 200,000 U.S. dollars as the overall
winner and 50,000 U.S. dollars for winning the final meet of the
season.
</P>
<P>
World pole vault legend Sergei Bubka of Ukraine excited the
crowd by winning the gold with a height of 6.05 meters.
</P>
<P>
Kumbernuss entered the Grand Prix finals tied for the overall
lead with Jamaica's Deon Hemmings, the women's 400 meters hurdle
champion at the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
But Hemmings's chance of the overall title disappeared when
she was upset in her race by American Kim Batten.
</P>
<P>
American Marion Jones, 21, edged past veteran Merlene Ottey of
Jamaica down the stretch to win the women's 200m in 21.84
seconds. Ottey finished second in 21.92.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF grand prix circuit is a worldwide tour of 27
meets. Top eight finishers in each event receive points based on
the results for the overall rankings. Points are tripled for the
season's final meet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
