<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Seizes 516 Kilograms of Uranium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has seized up to 516.56
kilograms of poor-grade uranium from smugglers or innocent holders
since October 1993, said a senior Vietnamese official.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Tien Nguyen, director of the eight-member Vietnam Atomic
Energy Commission (VAEC) said Friday that his committee has also
confiscated 268.65 kilograms of another substance first believed
to uranium.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory testing found that this substance was depleted
uranium, solid waste discharged in the process of enriching
uranium which has no economic value and cannot be used for making
atomic energy, Nguyen said.
</P>
<P>
He added that not a fraction of the dangerous u238 type has
been seized in the country so far.
</P>
<P>
The committee was formed years ago following international
concern that Vietnam was becoming a new venue for an international
black market trade for the uranium (u235) used for nuclear energy
production.
</P>
<P>
The AVEC director said that all the 65 confiscated objects
containing depleted uranium 235 were believed to have come the
United States as many of them bear the imprint "Made In USA."
</P>
<P>
They were possibly retrieved from U.S. aircraft downed in the
war which ended 22 years ago, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
