<HEADLINE> Moi Reiterates Commitment to End Violence in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi has reiterated the government's intention to end the
continuous violence taking place in the Coast Province during the
past five weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation today quoted the president as saying Friday
at a mass rally in West Province that the killers would face the
full force of the law.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported that Kenyan police had shot dead eight
suspected raiders in a recent operation to end the violence in
the port city of Mombasa and its environs.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Friday by Police Commissioner Duncan
Wachira said that a policeman was shot in the left arm and
security officers had recovered two G3 rifles, six rounds of
ammunition and two rifle magazines during the operation.
</P>
<P>
The police boss noted in the statement that 62 kenyans
including 10 policemen had been killed and 73 injured in the
five-week long violence in the Coast Province.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan police have lost 48 firearms, 1,496 bullets, one VHF
set and a walkie talkie in the incident of burn-down Likoni
Police Station in Mombasa on August 13, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wachira pointed out that Kenyan police had recovered 16
firearms, 238 bullets and 10 rifle magazines following an appeal
to surrender illegal arms to the government by President Moi.
</P>
<P>
In Mombasa, local police said that they arrested 27 suspects
in a two-hour gun battle with raiders on Thursday at Ukunda
township on the south coast of Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
The new coast provincial police boss Japheth Mwania, who is
leading a combined force of the General Service Unit, Regular and
Administration Police, and Nairobi-based Flying Squad, was quoted
as saying Friday that the raiders were still being pursued.
</P>
