<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More, Better Toilets Built in Rural Areas (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- A Xinhua reporter recently
visited toilets in a number of villages in south China to see the
effect of changes on the lives of farmers, who, for thousands of
years, have found relief in nothing more than a shallow pit.
</P>
<P>
In the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, farmers of ethnic
Zhuang group now have three types of toilets for rural
conditions: "the double-urn", the "little thriple-check", and the
"triple-union methane-producer".
</P>
<P>
"Rural residents are trying to change their image of paying
little attention to hygiene," said 57-year-old woman of Longlou
village in Fusui town, named Huang Chang'e, when she was taking
visitors on a tour of the toilet in her house.
</P>
<P>
"It really gives us a lot of convenience," Huang said, praising
the toilet at home, "We had to find some deserted spot up on the
hillside whenever we wanted to go to the bathroom and it was a real
nightmare for anyone with diarrhoea. But now those embarrassing
things never happen."
</P>
<P>
And, the family is going to build another toilet with a
methane-producing system, she pointed out grinned, showing a pile
of bricks and three pits in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
From there, the reporter went on to find more
examples. Villagers were busy moving in bricks, ceramic tile, and
other construction materials for different kinds of sanitary
toilets everywhere, toiling away enthusiastically, as if their
lives depended on it.
</P>
<P>
The 31 families in Shuangjia village have flush toilets in
bathrooms at home with ceramic tile walls and floors. And they're
rightly proud of these achievements. Explains one, "First,
convenience; second, cleanliness; third, organic fertilizer for
crops."
</P>
<P>
Now that villagers earn an average of 3,000 yuan (375 US
dollars) yearly it's not so difficult to build an 800-yuan toilet.
</P>
<P>
And, the toilet revolution may even help rural people earn more
money, because, in the past, the major problem faced by investors
from other parts of China, not to mention overseas, was finding a
good toilet, "So they lost interest in investing in our hometown,"
says one villager, Deng Xianfa, dejectedly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
