<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More, Better Toilets Built in Rural Areas (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Putting toilets in houses shows the emancipation of the mind
and a change in thinking," explains a village cadre, who notes
that many farmers used to be superstitious about building a toilet
in the home because it would bring bad luck. But now the toilet
craze in Guangxi is even attracting people from elsewhere who are
interested in getting some construction experience.
</P>
<P>
Wang Guoqing, the secretary of the Party Committee of Qujiu
Town, a town in another part of Guangxi, said, "We brought a
12-member-team here with the goal of learning how to build a
civilized village and protect the environment."
</P>
<P>
A 1992 autonomous regional Patriotic Hygiene Committee study of
25,163 rural families in the region, which has the largest ethnic
minority population in China, showed that 72.6 percent of them had
toilets. But only five percent met sanitary standards, so officials
concluded that greater efforts were required in renovating them if
the rural economy was to improve.
</P>
<P>
And regional and county government regard the construction of
hygiene facilities as one of the major criteria of the quality of
officials' work in villages.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous regional government has spent some seven million
yuan in past two years on sanitary toilets like the double-urn or
methane-producer in rural households. The county government is
offering an enamel basin and three bags of cement to farmers who
will build the toilet themselves.
</P>
<P>
"The regional government will continue this revolution in rural
lifestyle to help reach the country's goal for the year 2000 of 80
per cent of rural families having sanitary toilets," said Xie
Ping, deputy director of the local Patriotic Hygiene Committee.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
