<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Quarter S. Africans to be HIV Positive in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS epidemic in
South Africa would peak in the year 2005 when 25 percent of
adults would be HIV positive, Southern Life's AIDS Unit predicted
at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar, Janin Slawski, head of the unit, said
"AIDS will have its greatest impact on the 30-40 age group. The
sharp increase in deaths in this age group will cause the
national mortality rate to multiply five or six times."
</P>
<P>
Between a quarter and one third of children born to
HIV-positive mothers would be infected, she said, adding that
many babies would be infected by breast feeding.
</P>
<P>
"The community, government and non-governmental organizations
will have to work together to ensure a humane approach toward
AIDS children is developed," Slawski urged.
</P>
<P>
According to Slawski, South African Law Commission had put
forward a draft national policy on HIV and AIDS in schools. It
proposed that compulsory HIV testing for school applicants was
not justified, but recognized that special measures had to be
taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
