<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti PM to Return Home to Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Crown Prince and
Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdallah Al-Sabah will return home
from a long health recovery in London by the end of this month to
reshuffle his cabinet, a local newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
English daily Arab Times quoted highly informed sources who
asked not to be named as saying Saad's return would pave the
way for a major cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
The sources revealed the new cabinet is expected to include
several new faces with expanded authority. But they gave no direct
reasons for the talked reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Saad suffered a bleeding in the colon and undertook an
operation in March. Later he was flown to London where he
underwent further surgeries and has since then been recuperating
there.
</P>
<P>
It was revealed that Saad has prepared an action plan for the
country, based on all the events that took place during his
absence.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Saad will form a new cabinet to carry out
the new plan, and this will set fourth a new era in the local
politics.
</P>
<P>
They said that the new plan would be based on appointing
"strong and competent" members in the cabinet, who will not be
changed every four years in common practice.
</P>
<P>
The practice in Kuwait politics has been that cabinets and
ministers must be changed every four years to coincide
parliamentary elections. But the rule would be changed if the
reshuffle takes place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
