<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: India, Pakistan Ready to Continue Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Despite their grave
differences over the Kashmir issue, both India and Pakistan, the
two arch-rivals in South Asia, still want to continue their talks
in the interest of improving relations and enhancing economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
India Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral and his Pakistani
counterpart Nawaz Sharif are to meet in New York on September 24
as part of efforts to ensure that the recently initiated dialogue
between the two countries "remains on track."
</P>
<P>
The announcement about the Gujral-Sharif breakfast meeting in
New York was made by visiting Pakistani Information Minister
Mushahid Hussain after he met Gujral here on Friday. It has
cleared the air of uncertainty after initial hesitation for the
second summit meeting this year.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers met in the Maldives in May on the
sidelines of a summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC).
</P>
<P>
In that meeting, they reached an agreement
to continue their dialogues and set up several joint working
groups to iron out their main differences including the issue of
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Last night, India and Pakistan announced that the third round
of the foreign secretary-level talks between the two countries
would be held in New Delhi from September 15 to 18. The talks,
stalled for about three years due to their dispute over Kashmir,
were resumed in New Delhi in March this year and the second round
was held in Islamabad in June.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a group of students and teachers at the School of
International Studies of the Jawaharlal Nehru University here
Friday, Hussain said the Indo-Pakistan summit meeting in New York
was to ensure that dialogue remains on track and the core issue of
Jammu and Kashmir is discussed at the highest political level.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, there have been certain signals from Delhi that
the understanding arrived at on June 23 (during the second round
of foreign secretary-level talks) will not be fully acceptable to
India. There have been indications that India will no longer be
willing to focus on regional peace and security and Jammu and
Kashmir," Hussain said.
</P>
<P>
"But to say that these issues be kept frozen while agreeing to
set up working groups on the other six issues is a violation of
the letter and spirit of the agreement," Hussain said.
</P>
<P>
He described Kashmir as the "primary roadblock to the
normalization of relations between India and Pakistan, the core
issue which cannot be wished away."
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the summit meeting and the third round of
foreign secretary-level meeting between the two countries came in
the wake of Pakistan asking India to clarify whether it still
stands by the early joint statement by the foreign secretaries
providing for "focused discussions" on Kashmir and regional peace
and security.
</P>
<P>
The meetings are expected to clear the logjam in the foreign
secretary-level talks, which appeared to have reached an impasse
after some initial bonhomie.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
