<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of
the Crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week
mixed.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals closed the week higher. Against last week,
September South closed 5 ringgit (about 1.7 U.S. dollars) higher
at 1,365 ringgit (about 470.6 U.S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The easier ringgit, which eased to the 2.95 level at the close
after hovering between 2.88 and 2.89 level earlier in the week,
was one of the factors that has been influencing the uptrend of
crude palm oil prices, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian State Trading Corporation (STC) which tendered for
6,000 tons of Refined, Bleached and Deodorized (RBD) palm olein
for September 25 to October 5 and another 6,000 tons of RBD palm
olein for October 1 to 15 shipments, also aided market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
Private crop forecaster Ivan Wong forecasted that Malaysia's
August CPO production is estimated to increase by two percent to
850,000 tons over July's estimate.
</P>
<P>
Wong put end-August CPO stocks at 865,000 tons against 769,275
tons reported for July by the Palm Oil Registration and Licensing
Authority (PORLA).
</P>
<P>
This week, the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), started off
lower as the ringgit recovered its strength against the U.S.
dollar, but tin price improved thereafter as the ringgit slipped
against the greenback towards the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
Tin price ended the week at 15.66 ringgit (about 5.4 U.S.
dollars) per kg, unchanged from last week's close.
</P>
<P>
For the week, accumulated turnover rose to 545 tons from 468
tons last week with European and local buyers dominating the bulk
of the week's market transaction.
</P>
<P>
However, the Malaysian rubber market performed poorly despite
the weaker ringgit which failed to boost the commodity's price.
</P>
<P>
Most players opted to remain sidelined despite the fact that
Malaysian rubber has become cheaper due to the cheaper ringgit and
the fact that the commodity was in short supply due to the rainy
season in Malaysia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Against last week, October RSS One dipped eight sen to 256.50
sen (about 88.4 U.S. cents) per kg and SMR 20 fell by five sen to
257.00 sen (about 88.6 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
Sentiment on the local rubber market is expected to improve
next week as most European buyers are anticipated to return to the
market to seek fresh supply following the end of the long summer
holidays, a dealer said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Strike Called off in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's opposition lobby
group National Convention Executive Council (NCEC) has called off
a national strike set for next week with aims to press for total
constitutional reforms, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The NCEC was quoted as saying that it was calling off the
planned strike "to give Kenyans enough time to digest what has
been offered and tell us the way forward."
</P>
<P>
The move, seen as a swift turn-around, came after a majority
of parliamentary members reach a consensus on a landmark
political reforms package hammered into shape by the
Inter-Parties Parliamentary Group (IPPG) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the NCEC dismissed the package as a "gigantic fraud"
which would help retain President Daniel arap Moi in power.
</P>
<P>
Allowing a winning president to name ministers from all
parties, the IPPG package has given him the mandate to destroy
the opposition from parliament, NCEC spokesman Kivutha Kibwana
charged Friday.
</P>
<P>
What the IPPG did was to "merely skim the surface without
disturbing the basis status quo" of the political system of this
east African country, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the day, religious leaders gave an unequivocal green light
to the package, saying they would monitor the IPPG to ensure the
reforms process was successfully completed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
