<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka-Calcutta Bus Service May Start From December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Direct Dhaka-Calcutta bus
service is likely to begin from mid-December after signing of
motor vehicle agreement between Bangladesh and India, said
official sources today.
</P>
<P>
A 6-member team of officials from Indian Surface Transport
Ministry is due to arrive here on September 22 for working out
details of the bus link, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are to sign a memorandum of understanding at
their two-day meeting in Dhaka for opening this envisaged route,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Buses having Bangladeshi and Indian registration will be
allowed to operate directly, and passengers will not need to
disembark at any point between Dhaka and Calcutta after the route
opens.
</P>
<P>
Although travelers must hold passports and visas, the
procedures will be made easy, and customs and immigration check
will require only 10 to 15 minutes, the sources stated.
</P>
<P>
Around 100,000 passengers will avail of this bus service a
year, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
A maximum of 10 hours may be required to reach Dhaka from
Calcutta, taking into consideration of the Daulatdia-Aricha ferry
crossing, the sources said, adding that efforts will be made to
have special ferries for the buses plying on the Dhaka-Calcutta
route.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
