<HEADLINE> Chinese Investment Encouraged in Cameroun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Camerounian Prime Minister
Peter Mafany Musonge has encouraged Chinese investors to continue
their efforts in setting up an economic development zone in the
country.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement here Friday while meeting with Ye Jian,
chairman of the Foreign Economic and Trade Relation Commission of
Jiangsu Province, China.
</P>
<P>
Mudonge spoke highly of China's economic achievements, saying
China is a great country with a very fantastic growth rate in
Gross Domestic Products (GDP) which exceeds 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to benefit from your experience," he added.
</P>
<P>
The premier noted that the Camerounian government welcomes
Chinese businessmen to set up an economic development zone in the
country. This, he said, can provide more jobs for Camerounians
and is conducive to the technical transformation.
</P>
<P>
Ye Jian, head of the 19-man provincial business delegation to
the country, reviewed that the current working visit is designed
to examine the possibility of setting up an economic development
zone in Cameroun.
</P>
<P>
"Both our two countries' top leaders attach importance to
developing our economic cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming economic development zone will locate at Douala,
the economic capital of Cameroun, Ye noted, adding the industrial
sectors will play an important role in the zone, with certain
commercial service programs also initiated there.
</P>
<P>
"We shall choose those programs which are particularly
demanded in promoting the Camerounian economy," Ye said.
</P>
<P>
"We would also like to introduce our management systems and
bring about new ideas to Camerounian people," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Jiangsu business delegation arrived here on September 5.
During the week-long visit, the Chinese delegates met with
Cameroun's Minister of Trade and Industrial Development and
Minister of External Relations. They also held working sessions
with Camerounian senior trade officials and took a business tour
to Douala.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation will leave the country today for
Libreville, Gabon while some of the technicians in the delegation
will stay in the country to continue their examination work for
another two weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
