<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kipketer Claims Grand Prix Overall Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Danish runner Wilson Kipketer
won the overall title at the IAAF Grand Prix Final with another
win in the men's 800 meters at Fukuoka, Japan, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer, a Kenya-born Dane, clocked one minute 42.98 seconds
to win his final race of the season at Fukuoka.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer has not been been beaten in the distance since the
1995 Grand Prix Final.
</P>
<P>
patrick Ndururi of Kenya finished second at 1:43.45, followed
by his compatriot David Kiptoo in the third place at 1:44.69.
</P>
<P>
The win was Kipketer's 12th out of 12 starts this season,
including nine wins in the Grand Prix series and the world
championships in Athens last month.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer also set world indoor records twice at the Paris
world indoor championships in March and outdoor records three
times in Stockholm, Zurich and Cogogne in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
By winning the overall title, Kipketer received 200,000
dollars. He also got 50,000 dollars by winning the individual
event.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Keter of Kenya pulled off an upset in the 3,000 meters
steeplechase by beating top three world medallists Wilson Boit
Kipketer, Bernard Barmasai and Moses Kiptanui, who all come from
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Keter was timed at 8:21.75, a meter ahead of world silver
medallist Kiptanui who came in 8:21.87.
</P>
<P>
Women's Grand Prix points co-leader Deon Hemmings from Jamaica
failed to win the last race of the season and lost to American
world record holder Kim Batten in the 400 meters hurdles.
</P>
<P>
Batten clocked 53.45 and Hemmings finished at 53.98, followed
by Tatyana Tereshchuk of Ukraine at 54.37. 
</P>
</TEXT>
