<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Third Largest Party to Withdraw Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Former President of Bangladesh
HM Ershad on Friday castigated the incumbent government for
failure to run the country and said his party would not support it
any more, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ershad, Chairman of the third largest Jatiya (national) party
in Bangladesh, told a public meeting on central Tangail city that
his party would play the role of real opposition political party
from now.
</P>
<P>
"The Awami (people's) League (AL) in its 14-month reign didn't
do a single good work. There is no scope to support this
government," said Ershad, whose party lent support to the AL in
forming government and got a post in the cabinet after last year's
election.
</P>
<P>
Ershad said that he extended his support to the AL with the
hope that it would do better than the former ruling Bangladesh
Nationalist Party. But the AL did not fulfill its pledges to the
people it committed during its election campaign, he added.
</P>
<P>
The JP supremo also said that his party would withdraw
Secretary General Anwar Hossain Monju from the cabinet very soon,
and "he (Hossain Monju) pledged to do so".
</P>
<P>
The former military ruler, who was deposed through a mass
upheaval in 1990 after a nine-year rule, said there is no
alternative to JP to run the country.
</P>
<P>
"The JP is neither a pro-Pakistani nor pro-Indian party. It is
a real Bangladeshi and it will uphold the cause of Bangladeshi
people," claimed Ershad, adding that he hoped the JP will form the
next government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
