<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebels Discuss Guidelines for Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The peace negotiators of the
Philippine government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
rebels have started to make the implementing guidelines for the
general ceasefire agreement they signed in July.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency today quoted Al Haj Murad, MILF vice
chairman for military affairs, as saying that the two sides signed
an agreement after holding another round of low-level talks in
Cotabato city, the southern Philippines, on September 11-12.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the government and the MILF would
form their respective administrative committee to coordinate with
each other for the enforcement of the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also contained the composition, meetings, powers
and functions of the committees and the creation of an independent
fact-finding committee.
</P>
<P>
The agreement did not include the rules governing the conduct
of military forces and MILF rebels in battle fronts and neutral
grounds and the determination of truce violations.
</P>
<P>
The negotiators agreed to discuss the remaining issues at their
following meetings.
</P>
<P>
Murad was optimistic about the peace process. He even hinted
that a peace agreement between the MILF and the government would
be signed before President Fidel Ramos' term ends in June next
year.
</P>
<P>
MILF, a 12,000-member rebel group, was now the major block to
final peace in the southern Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 091387 S. Africa to Bid for 2008 Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will
participate in the bid to host the 2008 summer Olympics,
President Sam Ramsamy of National Olympic Committee of South
Africa (NOCSA) said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's 2008 Olympic bid would depend on local cities
submitting their separate bid by the year 2000, Ramsamy told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the fact that we failed in the recent bid, we still
did very well by coming third. It made our possibilities for
getting the games in 2008 greater," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town, the legislative capital of South Africa, came third
of the five cities competing for hosting the 2004 Olympic Games.
The city received 60 votes in the first round and 22 in the
second. In the third round, however, the votes in its favor were
eliminated to 20.
</P>
<P>
Once cities in the country applied to participate in the 2008
bid, said Ramsamy, the next step for NOCSA would be to evaluate
the cities according to the Olympic charter of the International
Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
"We need to look at why Athens won and learn lessons from the
bid winning city," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides Athens and Cape Town, Rome, Stockholm and Buenos Aires
were among the final bidding cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Hails Zambia's Economic Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
European Union has commended Zambia for its economic policies
which are described as being positive toward attaining a
sustainable national economy.
</P>
<P>
Officiating a training and consultancy workshop in Lusaka
Friday, Charles Brook, head of a delegation of the EU commission,
said Zambia's economy has great potential and stood a chance of
performing well, Zambia's Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a financial assistance of 138 million U.S.
Dollars to be given to African, Caribbean and Pacific countries
(ACP), Brook said at the closing of the two-week workshop that EU
should have loved Zambia to move at a faster rate in implementing
its economic policies.
</P>
<P>
He added that a bulk of the EU grant would go to the areas
which the Zambian government has attached top priority when
addressing social problems such as gender issues, poverty and
illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
The workshop held here as well as in other countries is part
of the EU program which aims at training 200 EU commission staff
and their counterparts in 10 African countries to strengthen a
network of experts in gender consultancy and training in these
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
