<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reasonable Prices for Zambia's Copper Mines Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has urged the bidder
of the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) to offer
reasonable prices for ZCCM assets.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Ronald Penza said in a special business
review program on Zambian National Broadcasting Corporation
(ZNBC) Friday night that mining remains a major component of the
country's economy as such ZCCM needs to be sold at the best price
offer.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia quoted him as saying that "I urge parties
negotiating to pay reasonable assets prices and commit a long-term
program of reinvestment."
</P>
<P>
Penza also called on southern African countries to strengthen
regional integration and allow free flow of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent reference to Dunlop, a victim of competition
from heavily subsidized South African imports, he blamed some
countries in the region for being too slow to remove tariffs.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia is way ahead and could not apply the same rules
as the countries are subsidizing goods.
</P>
<P>
"Unless we go into regional integration and allow relative
comparative advantage to determine the flow of goods and
services, the region as a whole is going to suffer," he said.
</P>
<P>
Penza was particularly disappointed with Dunlop management for
lacking patience even after it agreed to suspend closure until
appropriate tariffs for imports are introduced.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed to work on safeguard measures in order to ensure we
do not ban but apply appropriate tariffs. I would have expected
Dunlop to have waited for parliament to sit," the minister said.
</P>
</TEXT>
