<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Defense Minister to Visit S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia's Defense
and Aviation Minister Sultan Adbulaziz Al-Saudi would visit South
Africa from September 23 to 29, the Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Abudulaziz, who is also the Kingdom's second Deputy Prime
Minister, would hold talks with President Nelson Mandela, his
South African counterpart Joe Modise and several other government
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and South Africa are finalizing a 1.5 billion
U.S. Dollars deal for the sale of G6 motorized artillery pieces
and anti-aircraft weapon systems.
</P>
<P>
It is the largest arms deal in South African history and is
expected to create 30,000 jobs over five years.
</P>
<P>
The controversial arms deal hit the headlines in July when
Denel, the country's major arms manufacturer, sought an interim
court order to prohibit newspapers from identifying Saudi Arabia
as the client country.
</P>
<P>
However, local media ignored the court order and identified
the Middle Eastern country. Its name had already been published
abroad. The crisis had jeopardized the deal as the
confidentiality clause of the proposed deal had been violated.
</P>
<P>
South African human rights and foreign policy opponents of the
deal argue that the country should not sell arms to the world's
most volatile region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
