<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Retreat from Opposition Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia have retreated from the opposition stronghold of
Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km north of capital of Kabul, Afghan
sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Taliban fighters lost control of Mazar-e-Sharif airport, about
18 km east of the city, on Friday evening under vigorous
counter-attacks by their rival alliance forces, the Afghan sources
here confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The front-line now was shifted to about two km east of the
Mazar-e-Sharif airport, they said, adding the order in the
northern major city was restored after three days of looting.
</P>
<P>
"The city is much calmer, and people are back to the streets,"
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Mazar-e-Sharif, the second largest city in Afghanistan, now
serves as headquarters of the anti-Taliban alliance, which
comprises forces loyal to Uzbek warlord Abdul Malik, former
military chief Ahmad Masood and Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat.
</P>
<P>
In Kabul, a 10-year-old girl was killed and two women injured
today when a heavy rocket fired at the Afghan capital's airport
overshot the perimeter and struck a farming area, according to a
report monitored here.
</P>
<P>
The airport is being used as an air base for Taliban to supply
troops battling near Mazar-e-Sharif. So far none of the rockets
have hit the airport.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two months, anti-Taliban forces under Masood's
command have been battling the hard-line militia in front lines
only 25 km north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, which control two thirds of the Afghan territory
and capital of Kabul, have vowed to impose strict Islamic rule in
the war-torn country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
