<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15,000 Congolese Refugees to Go Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Another batch of
Congolese (K) refugees numbering some 15,000 will be voluntarily
repatriated to their homeland by October this year, according to
a news dispatch reaching here from Kigoma today.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement for the repatriation is under a tripartite
agreement reached among the Democratic Republic of Congo,
Tanzania and the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR) on August 20 in Dar es Salaam, the report quoted UNHCR
officials in Kigoma, western Tanzania, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian refugee camps have hosted 74,000 Congolese refugees
at Kasulu and Lugufu in Kigoma Region. Already, 1,124 refugees
have left for Congo (K) since September 2 under the tripartite
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Michael Phillips, a UNHCR representative in the Congolese
district of Uvira was quoted as saying that returning refugees
should not worry of their lives as "everything is under control,
all those who have returned have been sent to heir home villages
and are enjoying life there."
</P>
<P>
"We haven't received any complaints from the refugees. They
are happy at home," said Phillips who accompanied the returning
refugees aboard a ship in Lake Tanganyiga early this month.
</P>
<P>
The new administration in Congo (K) has appealed to returning
refugees to bury their political and ethnic differences and come
out together to rebuild the nation which had been ravaged by
civil war and political uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming the returning refugees last week, Uvira
District Commissioner Bashire Kusebana appealed to them to love
one another in this time of reconstruction of Congo (K). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
