<HEADLINE> India's Congress Leader Plans UF Government Ouster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- India's Congress President
Sitaram Kesri has decided to examine the possibility of
withdrawing support from the United Front (UF) government headed
by Inder Kumar Gujral around February next year, a local English
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Congress is expected not to allow the UF government to pass
the next budget early next year, the Statesman quoted senior
Congress leaders as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to senior party leaders, Kesri will be sending
central observers to every state to solicit the views of the
party's local units on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Kesri himself believes that if the present government is
allowed to pass one more budget, that would make the Congress
weaker as it will not be in a position to avoid the responsibility
of any downslide in the economy. He also believes that the UF may
not be in a position to stay together till February next year.
</P>
<P>
The Congress supports the 13-party UF government from the
outside. As the UF government is a minority coalition, it will
immediately fall if the Congress withdraws its support. In March
this year, the UF government headed by Deve Gowda stepped down
following the withdrawal of support by the Congress, and the
Gujral government took office the next month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
