<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Prolonged profit-taking
gave way to bargain-hunting which propelled the Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange to close stronger this week.
</P>
<P>
A sudden surge of more than 200-points in just two trading days
after the government lifted the designated status of the Composite
Index 100-components on September 4 prompted a strong correction
this week with the market well supported at above the 800-level.
</P>
<P>
The 100-quality stocks Composite Index jumped 30.49 points to
852.08, the all-share Emas Index gained 11.70 points to 242.88,
the Industrial Index was 89.82 points higher at 1,747.40 while the
Second Board Index surged 44.90 points to 445.91.
</P>
<P>
The week saw profit-taking taking its toll on prices for most
of the trading days. Analysts and dealers said the profit-taking
was justified as players were trying to minimize recent losses.
</P>
<P>
Foreign funds were cautious in trading as they were concerned
over Malaysia's macro-economic picture especially on the current
account deficit (CAD).
</P>
<P>
On September 10, Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim
announced that government expenditure will be reduced by two
percent, mega projects will be deferred and that all new
privatized projects and purchase of foreign goods will be
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
The government's measures are heading towards the right
direction and confidence is slowly seeping back into the market
following the launch of the one billion ringgit (about 344.8
million U.S. dollars) government bonds, part of the 60 billion
ringgit (over 20 billion U.S. dollars) package announced recently
to shore up the local bourse, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
They are optimistic the market will breach the 880 points level
or even the 900 points level next week for a more convincing
upturn.
</P>
<P>
This week saw one leading self adhesive label converter --
Komarkcorp Bhd -- making its debut on the market and three
counters -- Tongkah, TSH Resources and Pantai Hospital --
suspended.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the mainboard volume was slightly higher at
1.901 billion shares worth 8.433 billion ringgit (about 2.9
billion U.S. dollars) from 1.802 billion shares valued at 7.035
billion ringgit (about 2.4 billion U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover stood at 316.012 million shares
valued at 2.672 billion ringgit (about 921 million U.S. dollars)
against last week's 167.200 million shares worth 1.326 billion
ringgit (about 457 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals amounted to 145.903 million shares worth
810.166 million ringgit (about 279 million U.S. dollars) against
165.428 million shares valued at 625.819 million ringgit (about
215 million U.S. dollars) at last week's close.
</P>
<P>
Consumer products accounted for 143.638 million shares traded,
industrial products 220.046 million, construction 217.167 million,
trading/services 443.518 million, infrastructure 10.617 million,
finance 363.967 million, hotels 8.505 million, properties 240.065
million, plantation 40.284 million, mining 12.061 million, trusts
1.727 million, closed/fund 1.055 million and loan stocks 205.733
million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
