<HEADLINE> Nuclear Non-Proliferation Conference Ends in Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The process of nuclear
non-proliferation is an important guarantee for world peace and
security, said the international nuclear non-proliferation
conference that ended today.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 officials and nuclear experts from Russia, the
United States, France, Germany, Ukraine and other Central Asian
countries attended the five-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The conference discussed rules of conduct regarding the
production and storage of nuclear weapons, nuclear
non-proliferation technology and nuclear safety.
</P>
<P>
The representatives also visited a large, now closed, nuclear
testing ground of the former Soviet Union, located in
Semipalatinskya Obl, to study how to wipe out nuclear pollution
there.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the conference, U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan said that the conference would play an important role in the
eventual, global destruction of nuclear weapons and promote the
setting up of a nuclear-free zone in Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Turkmenistan, Tajikistan and Uzbekistan
signed a joint declaration to establish a nuclear-free zone in
Central Asia in April this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
