<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gelbard Reaffirms U.S. Support for Bosnia's Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. special envoy Robert
Gelbard has reaffirmed U.S. support for the municipal elections in
Bosnia due to be held in September 13 and 14.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard, after his meeting with Bosnian Serb President Biljana
Plavsic Friday night in Banja Luka, said that international
community only provides aid for those making full implementation
of the 1995 Dayton peace accords and taking an active part in the
coming municipal elections in Bosnia, which he believed will be
"free and fair."
</P>
<P>
Serbs, Muslims and Croats will vote for 136 municipalities in
the two-day elections, which have been postponed twice.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Serbs and Croat once threatened to boycott the
elections, but Plavsic said she expected the polls to take
place in a quiet atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Interior Ministry of the Bosnian Serb Republic
in Pale announced today that the Ministry has taken every measure
necessary to ensure safe elections in accordance with the Dayton
accords.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard also said that the U.S. will continue to support the
early elections for Bosnian Serb parliament, which Plavsic
dissolved in July, a move rejected by her rivals in Bosnian Serb
parliament and government.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Serb Constitutional Court declared in August the
dissolution of parliament by Plavsic "does not conform with the
constitution" and was thus "invalid." 
</P>
</TEXT>
