<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ailing Economy Hits Thai Printing Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's economic slump may
force one-third of the country's printing houses, including
publishers of newspapers and magazines, to close down, according
to a report of the Thai Farmers' Research Center.
</P>
<P>
Publishers are now faced with three main problems -- falling
circulation, dwindling advertising and rising costs.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two years, four daily newspapers, including the
English-language Asia Times and Thailand Times, have folded.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all existing newspapers are making internal adjustments
to survive.
</P>
<P>
About 120,000 of the sector's 800,000 workers have been laid
off and 30 percent have had their salaries reduced, the center
said in a recent report.
</P>
<P>
Some publishing companies have cut back welfare payments,
bonuses and overseas coverage trips and closed overseas bureaus
and are controlling more tightly newsprint use.
</P>
<P>
The prices of imported pulp, paper and ink have soared
following the floatation and depreciation of the Thai currency.
</P>
<P>
Advertising revenue, the industry's main source of income, has
also taken a sharp dive, as companies such as property developers
have dramatically trimmed their advertising budgets, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Classified ad in some newspapers has shrunk to about a dozen
pages from about two dozens or more.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
