<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, September 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and Chief Executive
Tung Chee Hwa of Hong Kong Special Administrative Region met here
Friday, emphasizing the importance of a good US-Chinese
relationship.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting at the White House,
Tung said that he had a "warm and cordial" meeting with Clinton at
the Oval Office. (US-Tung-Clinton)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- A French judge on Friday issued the permit for burying
the body of Henri Paul, the chauffeur of Princess Diana, after
having made three toxicological examinations on it.
(France-Diana-Chauffeur)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Workers in Worri, a major oil production base in
southeastern Nigeria, on Friday held hostage more than 70 people,
including 12 foreigners, for improvement in their working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
They did so to protest over the term of employment and
negotiations are underway, according to a statement of the
American oil company Mobil.
</P>
<P>
The people held are reportedly working for Mobil operating in
Nigeria. The foreigners, from Britain, the United States, Ireland
and other countries, are safe, diplomat sources said.
(Nigieria-hostage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUDAPEST -- Vice President of the World Bank Johannes Linn
declared here Friday that the bank will provide 600 million
U.S. dollars to Hungary for its projects in the next three
years. (World Bank-Hungary Loan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Thirty-nine bomb threats have been recorded in Metro
Manila and the provinces recently, the Philippine Daily Inquirer
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said at least 11 bomb threats had been recorded
in Metro Manila alone in the past two days, forcing evacuation of
government employees and prompting police to ask for the help of a
telephone company in tracing the threat callers.
</P>
<P>
The targets of the threats included the building of the
Department of Social Welfare and Development, the office of
vice-mayor of Quezon city and the Pasig City Hall.
(Philippines-Bomb Threats) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
