<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mobile Opens New Lubricant Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The American-based Mobile Oil
Corp has opened a new lubricant blending plant in Taicang City in
east China's Jiangsu Province, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The plant, with an annual production capacity of 500,000
barrels of lubricants, is Mobile's largest in China. It is also
one of the world's few most advanced plants in terms of production
technology.
</P>
<P>
"It marks a new era for Mobile's long-term investment in
China," said Lucio Noto, Chairman and CEO of Mobile Corp.
</P>
<P>
The plant has been accredited ISO 9002 quality system
certification for its facilities and products, the first for a
foreign-funded firms in petrochemical industry in China.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Taicang plant, Mobile operates two lubricant
manufacturing plants in Tianjin and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Mobile has become China's leading international lubricant
supplier and merchandiser of premium petroleum products, It has
opened over 20 area offices in major Chinese cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Banker Warns Over Baht Volatility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The baht will remain volatile
if it does not settle in the range of 34 to 35 to the U.S. dollar,
a senior Thai bank executive warned.
</P>
<P>
The factors affecting the currency's value include the Thai
central bank's offshore swap obligations that come due over the
next 12 months, said Maleekanya Sagarik, vice-president of Union
Bank of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The future of the new constitution will also have an impact on
the baht, she was quoted as saying by the local newspaper The
Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
Last month, foreign creditors suspended credit lines to local
businesses because they lacked confidence in the country's
economy, but Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh's pledge to
accept the new constitution softened their stand and enable the
baht to recover this week, she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America Tops World in Privatization Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Some 750 state
enterprises worth a total of 130 billion U.S. dollars were
privatized in Latin America from 1988 to 1995, making the region
the world's leader in privatization, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
A Brazilian privatizing program for the next three years, the
biggest one in the world, will enable the region to maintain its
world leadership in privatizing progress, the press quoted French
and Brazilian Bank President Sergio de Freitas as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, Brazil will sell 80 billion dollars worth of
national enterprises to private ownership in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Southern Common Market countries, grouping Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay, claim 25 percent of all programs of
privatization in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rupiah Recovers, Stock Price Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's rupiah recovered
from early lows against the U.S. dollar Friday as the stock
exchange lost 1.7 percent, dealers and brokers said here today.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah closed up at 2,930/2,936 from an opening of 2,950/
2,960 in very thin trade as most banks did not open new positions
at the weekend, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta stock exchange composite index, the main price
indicator on the exchange, dropped by 9.490 points to close at
546.637.
</P>
<P>
Securities dealers attributed the decline to heavy selling
pressures by foreign investors in the market.
</P>
<P>
"Most foreign investors are net sellers," a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The government has lowered rates for the central bank's
short-term certificate (SBI) papers, but investors want it to be
lowered further and quickly, he said.
</P>
<P>
SBI is short-term rupiah-denominated obligations issued by the
central bank to drain liquidity from the market.
</P>
<P>
Local bank dealers said the central bank might cut its SBI
rates again next week.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has fallen more than 10 percent in the past month
and nearly 23 percent since January this year following offshore
speculative attacks on the currency and the rush by local
companies to hedge their foreign borrowings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Promises Investors Big Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Trade officials of south
China's Guangdong Province, promised local foreign-funded firms
big profits if they upgrade their operations.
</P>
<P>
"If offshore companies bring in advanced technology and
equipment and improve their management, I promises they will earn
more money in the prosperous Guangdong Province," today's China
Daily quoted an official from the Provincial Commission of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation as saying.
</P>
<P>
the official made the promise after a Sino-foreign joint
venture was auctioned off early this week in Zhanjiang, a port
city in Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
The Zhanjiang Sino-American Chemical Industrial Co., Ltd, based
in Zhanjiang City on the Leizhou Peninsula, went bankrupt last
November due to poor management, and has become the first
Sino-foreign joint venture to be auctioned off this year in
Guangdong since the Auction Law was introduced, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has established a framework for a market economy, and
encourages fair competition for both domestic and overseas
companies.
</P>
<P>
Most of the province's 61,000 foreign-funded firms and joint
ventures are earning money from the prosperous and growing market,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment is believed to have helped Guangdong's
economic takeoff which allows it compete with Southeast Asian
economies and other provinces and municipalities in
China. Overseas investment in Guangdong accounts for about one
forth of the country's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
