<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAEA Adopts Conventions on Liability for Atomic Damages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- A five-day conference of the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) ended here today with
the adoption of two conventions on liability for atomic damages.
</P>
<P>
The active international laws concerning liability for atomic
damages were adopted in 1960 and 1963, and cannot keep up with the
development of the situation.
</P>
<P>
The documents were drafted by a committee set up by the IAEA
and they were completed earlier this year after eight years of
work.
</P>
<P>
The two new international conventions will be open for signing
as of September 29.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 81 countries and five international
organizations attended the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Parliament Leaders Support Draft Charter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Thai Parliament President Wan
Mohammad Nor Matha and Senator Speaker Meechai Ruchuphan have
expressed their support for a move to amend the draft
constitution, but said any amendment should be made only after it
is passed by parliament.
</P>
<P>
Wan Nor said on Friday that once the new constitution is
promulgated, points that need to be changed should be changed.
</P>
<P>
Meechai also said on Friday that the draft constitution is
written somehow recklessly and there will be some problems when it
is in force.
</P>
<P>
But Meechai warned Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh's
government against attempting to amend the draft charter before
the final parliamentary vote, insisting that it should be changed
later.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit has reportedly been forced to agree to give support to
the draft constitution to avoid political conflicts in the
country, but he insisted the draft should be revised after the
parliament approves it.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers today reported that most of the parliament
members who opposed the draft charter have also agreed to pass it
late this month to avoid a tense political atmosphere in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
