<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Loan for Thai Infrastructure Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
agreed to extend a loan of about 106 billion yen (883 million US
dollars) for 10 infrastructure projects in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The loan and guarantees are scheduled for signing on September
30 when the two countries will sign a financial cooperation
agreement, according to the Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
The loan would be made through Japan's overseas economic
cooperation fund, which provides low-interest fund annually for
Thailand, now totalling 1,316 billion yen (11 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new loan will be used to finance projects such as an
electricity distribution system, a Bangkok subway, the new Bangkok
airport, a Bangkok ring road, a bridge over the Chao Phraya River
and credit for rural development.
</P>
<P>
The repayment period would be 25 years, instead of 20, and the
interest rate would be less than the 2-3 percent range that
applied to the previous loans, according to Finance Ministry
Permanent Secretary Suppachai Visitvanich.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
