<HEADLINE> Chile's National Copper Firm's Tax Contribution Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The National Copper
Corporation of Chile (Codelco) paid a total tax of 682 million
U.S. dollars during the first six months of 1997, which is 2
percent less than in the same period of 1996, the company said
today.
</P>
<P>
However, the volume of copper that was produced from January to
June, totalled 691,701 metric tons, representing an increase of
9.2 percent compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Income from copper sales amounted to 1.686 billion dollars, up
from 1.349 billion in the comparable 1966 period.
</P>
<P>
Byproducts sales produced 157 million dollars, which surpassed
the 131 million dollars obtained in the similar 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
Codelco invested 421 million dollars during the first six
months this year, far surpassing the 188 million dollars of the
same period of last year, to develop two projects, which are
expected to double its capacity of copper exploitation and
treatment.
</P>
<P>
The company predicted a rise in copper and concentrate export
for this year. Last year, 2.95 million tons were exported,
bringing in 5.88 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
