<HEADLINE> 39 Bomb Threats Recorded in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-nine bomb threats have
been recorded in Metro Manila and the provinces recently, the
Philippine Daily Inquirer reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said at least 11 bomb threats had been recorded
in Metro Manila alone in the past two days, forcing evacuation of
government employees and prompting police to ask for the help of a
telephone company in tracing the threat callers.
</P>
<P>
The targets of the threats included the building of the
Department of Social Welfare and Development, the office of
vice-mayor of Quezon city, the Pasig City Hall and some private
buildings and schools, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Recaredo Sarmiento, director of the Philippine
National Police, as saying that those behind the rash of bomb
threats were "sadists who derive happiness in seeing our people
cower in fear."
</P>
<P>
Another high-ranking police official in Quezon city said the
bomb threats could have been sent by crime syndicates which hoped
to draw away the attention of the police from their real
objectives.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some people say the threats were made by President
Fidel Ramos' supporters who wish to give Ramos a chance to declare
martial law by sending the country into chaos.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has categorically denied that he would impose martial law
in the country while keeping anyone guessing whether he would seek
a second term next year.
</P>
<P>
Some one million people would hold a grant rally in Metro
Manila on September 21 to voice their anger over Charter change
moves seeking to extend the term of President Ramos. It was
reported that some people had threatened to bomb the rally.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine police are still investigating two blasts in
which six people were killed and 55 others wounded last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
