<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Seize Counterfeit Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Police seized 300,000 forged
100 U.S. dollar bills in the southern city of Kurdjali Thursday,
the Bulgarian Telegraph Agency (BTA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Two Bulgarians and a Turkish national were arrested in the bust.
</P>
<P>
Police, citing initial interrogation, said the bills, which do
not have a security thread, were made in Turkey and smuggled into
Bulgaria in a tourist coach.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish national, Alaitin Dilmen, 50, was last detained in
January at a checkpoint on the Bulgarian-Turkish border for
attempted illegal export of 20,000 U.S. dollars. He is under an
effective two-year suspended sentence.
</P>
<P>
Kiril Radev, chief of the Central Service for Organized Crime
Control, said the Thursday raid broke up the international
counterfeit money ring, which channeled large sums of fake dollar
bills to Western Europe and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
