<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Exceptional Assistance to Bolivia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today announced the approval of exceptional assistance
for Bolivia under the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC)
initiative.
</P>
<P>
The exceptional assistance to be provided by all creditors will
reduce the external debt of Bolivia by 448 million U.S. dollars in
net present value (NPV) terms, of which the IMF will contribute
some 29 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The total nominal debt-service relief is estimated at some 600
million dollars. This compares to a debt in NPV terms of 3.4
billion dollars and involves a debt reduction of around 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
The IMF exceptional assistance of 29 million dollars in NPV
terms will be provided at the completion point in the form of a
grant into an escrow account to be used exclusively to pay debt
service to the IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970913.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Edge Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street edged
higher today, helped by some encouraging economic data.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 81.99 points to 7,742.97.
The gain cut the blue chip average's loss to 79.44 points for the
week.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by more than 5-to-2
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaling
543.33 million shares as against 574.57 million on the Thursday
session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 11.32 to 923.91, the
NYSE composite index rose 6.24 to 483.30, and the Nasdaq composite
index rose 9.47 to 1,649.33.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies closed at a record
high, rising 4.16 to 440.09. Also setting a new record was the
American Stock Exchange composite index, which rose 5.47 to
672.31.
</P>
<P>
Stocks drew an early boost from the bond market, where interest
rates fell sharply after the release of two reports showing a
modest increase in wholesale prices and a smaller-than-expected
increase in retail sales.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported that wholesale prices paid to
factories and other producers climbed just 0.3 percent in August.
It was the first increase since December.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the Commerce Department reported that retail
sales rose 0.4 percent in August, the third straight gain this
Summer after a cool spring kept shoppers at home.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
